INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-budgeting-1','finance','finance:budgeting','finance-budgeting-1','beginner','mcq','What is the main purpose of a personal budget?','What is the main purpose of a personal budget?',ARRAY['To plan how your income is allocated to spending and saving','To guarantee your investments earn a higher return','To remove the need to ever track your expenses again','To increase your credit limit with lenders']::text[],ARRAY['To plan how your income is allocated to spending and saving','To guarantee your investments earn a higher return','To remove the need to ever track your expenses again','To increase your credit limit with lenders']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A budget is a plan that maps your income against your spending and saving so you can direct your money intentionally.','A budget is a plan that maps your income against your spending and saving so you can direct your money intentionally.','A budget is simply a plan for where your money goes over a period, usually a month. It helps you make sure essential needs are covered, debts are paid, and some money is set aside for goals before discretionary spending. Reviewing it regularly lets you spot overspending early and adjust before it becomes a problem.','A budget is simply a plan for where your money goes over a period, usually a month. It helps you make sure essential needs are covered, debts are paid, and some money is set aside for goals before discretionary spending. Reviewing it regularly lets you spot overspending early and adjust before it becomes a problem.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-budgeting-2','finance','finance:budgeting','finance-budgeting-2','intermediate','mcq','In the popular 50/30/20 budgeting guideline, what does the 20% portion represent?','In the popular 50/30/20 budgeting guideline, what does the 20% portion represent?',ARRAY['Savings and debt repayment beyond minimums','Rent and other housing costs','Discretionary ''wants'' like dining out','Taxes withheld from your paycheck']::text[],ARRAY['Savings and debt repayment beyond minimums','Rent and other housing costs','Discretionary ''wants'' like dining out','Taxes withheld from your paycheck']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Under the 50/30/20 guideline, 50% goes to needs, 30% to wants, and 20% to savings and extra debt repayment.','Under the 50/30/20 guideline, 50% goes to needs, 30% to wants, and 20% to savings and extra debt repayment.','The 50/30/20 rule is a simple framework that splits after-tax income into three buckets: needs, wants, and savings or debt paydown. It is meant as a starting point rather than a strict law, and the percentages can be adjusted to fit your situation. Its value is in forcing you to consciously reserve a slice for your future rather than spending everything you earn.','The 50/30/20 rule is a simple framework that splits after-tax income into three buckets: needs, wants, and savings or debt paydown. It is meant as a starting point rather than a strict law, and the percentages can be adjusted to fit your situation. Its value is in forcing you to consciously reserve a slice for your future rather than spending everything you earn.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-budgeting-3','finance','finance:budgeting','finance-budgeting-3','advanced','mcq','A common guideline suggests an emergency fund should cover roughly how much of your living expenses?','A common guideline suggests an emergency fund should cover roughly how much of your living expenses?',ARRAY['Three to six months of essential expenses','One week of expenses','Two full years of expenses','Exactly one month''s rent']::text[],ARRAY['Three to six months of essential expenses','One week of expenses','Two full years of expenses','Exactly one month''s rent']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Most guidance recommends keeping three to six months of essential living costs in an accessible emergency fund to cover income loss or surprise bills.','Most guidance recommends keeping three to six months of essential living costs in an accessible emergency fund to cover income loss or surprise bills.','An emergency fund is cash set aside specifically for unexpected events like job loss, medical bills, or urgent repairs. Holding three to six months of essential expenses is a common target, with people in less stable jobs leaning toward the higher end. Because the point is quick access without loss of value, this money is usually kept in a safe, liquid account rather than invested in volatile assets.','An emergency fund is cash set aside specifically for unexpected events like job loss, medical bills, or urgent repairs. Holding three to six months of essential expenses is a common target, with people in less stable jobs leaning toward the higher end. Because the point is quick access without loss of value, this money is usually kept in a safe, liquid account rather than invested in volatile assets.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-credit-1','finance','finance:credit','finance-credit-1','beginner','truefalse','Paying your credit card balance in full and on time each month generally helps build a positive credit history.','Paying your credit card balance in full and on time each month generally helps build a positive credit history.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Consistent, on-time payments are one of the strongest positive signals in a credit history, and paying in full also avoids interest charges.','Consistent, on-time payments are one of the strongest positive signals in a credit history, and paying in full also avoids interest charges.','Payment history is typically the single most important factor in a credit score. Paying at least the minimum on time avoids late marks, but paying the full statement balance also means you avoid interest entirely. Over time, a record of reliable payments demonstrates to lenders that you are a low-risk borrower.','Payment history is typically the single most important factor in a credit score. Paying at least the minimum on time avoids late marks, but paying the full statement balance also means you avoid interest entirely. Over time, a record of reliable payments demonstrates to lenders that you are a low-risk borrower.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-credit-2','finance','finance:credit','finance-credit-2','intermediate','mcq','Credit utilization, an important factor in many credit scores, measures what?','Credit utilization, an important factor in many credit scores, measures what?',ARRAY['The share of your available revolving credit that you are currently using','The total number of years your oldest account has been open','How many different lenders have ever checked your credit','The interest rate charged on your largest loan']::text[],ARRAY['The share of your available revolving credit that you are currently using','The total number of years your oldest account has been open','How many different lenders have ever checked your credit','The interest rate charged on your largest loan']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Credit utilization is the ratio of your current revolving balances to your total available credit limits.','Credit utilization is the ratio of your current revolving balances to your total available credit limits.','Credit utilization compares how much revolving credit you are using to how much you have available, expressed as a percentage. Lower utilization generally signals that you are not overly reliant on borrowed money, which tends to support a higher score. A common rule of thumb is to keep utilization well below 30%, and paying balances down before the statement closes can help.','Credit utilization compares how much revolving credit you are using to how much you have available, expressed as a percentage. Lower utilization generally signals that you are not overly reliant on borrowed money, which tends to support a higher score. A common rule of thumb is to keep utilization well below 30%, and paying balances down before the statement closes can help.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-credit-3','finance','finance:credit','finance-credit-3','advanced','mcq','When tackling several debts, what distinguishes the ''debt avalanche'' method from the ''debt snowball'' method?','When tackling several debts, what distinguishes the ''debt avalanche'' method from the ''debt snowball'' method?',ARRAY['The avalanche targets the highest interest rate first, while the snowball targets the smallest balance first','The avalanche targets the smallest balance first, while the snowball targets the highest rate first','The avalanche pays only minimums while the snowball skips minimums','Both methods always pay the largest balance first']::text[],ARRAY['The avalanche targets the highest interest rate first, while the snowball targets the smallest balance first','The avalanche targets the smallest balance first, while the snowball targets the highest rate first','The avalanche pays only minimums while the snowball skips minimums','Both methods always pay the largest balance first']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The avalanche prioritizes the highest interest rate to minimize total interest, while the snowball prioritizes the smallest balance to build motivation through quick wins.','The avalanche prioritizes the highest interest rate to minimize total interest, while the snowball prioritizes the smallest balance to build motivation through quick wins.','Both strategies have you pay minimums on every debt and then put extra money toward one target debt. The avalanche method attacks the highest interest rate first, which mathematically minimizes the total interest you pay. The snowball method attacks the smallest balance first, producing faster psychological wins that can help people stay motivated even if it costs slightly more in interest.','Both strategies have you pay minimums on every debt and then put extra money toward one target debt. The avalanche method attacks the highest interest rate first, which mathematically minimizes the total interest you pay. The snowball method attacks the smallest balance first, producing faster psychological wins that can help people stay motivated even if it costs slightly more in interest.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-investing-1','finance','finance:investing','finance-investing-1','beginner','mcq','What does it mean to diversify an investment portfolio?','What does it mean to diversify an investment portfolio?',ARRAY['Spreading money across many different investments to reduce risk','Putting all your money into a single promising company','Only investing during years when markets are rising','Borrowing money to increase the size of your bets']::text[],ARRAY['Spreading money across many different investments to reduce risk','Putting all your money into a single promising company','Only investing during years when markets are rising','Borrowing money to increase the size of your bets']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Diversification spreads your money across many assets so that a poor result from any one of them has a smaller impact on the whole.','Diversification spreads your money across many assets so that a poor result from any one of them has a smaller impact on the whole.','Diversification is the practice of holding a variety of investments rather than concentrating in one place. Because different assets often do not move in lockstep, a loss in one can be offset by gains or stability in others, smoothing overall results. It does not eliminate risk, but it reduces the chance that a single bad outcome devastates your portfolio.','Diversification is the practice of holding a variety of investments rather than concentrating in one place. Because different assets often do not move in lockstep, a loss in one can be offset by gains or stability in others, smoothing overall results. It does not eliminate risk, but it reduces the chance that a single bad outcome devastates your portfolio.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-investing-2','finance','finance:investing','finance-investing-2','intermediate','mcq','A broad-market index fund is generally designed to do what?','A broad-market index fund is generally designed to do what?',ARRAY['Track the performance of a whole market index at low cost','Beat the market by frequently picking individual winning stocks','Guarantee a fixed return regardless of market conditions','Hold only a single company''s stock for maximum focus']::text[],ARRAY['Track the performance of a whole market index at low cost','Beat the market by frequently picking individual winning stocks','Guarantee a fixed return regardless of market conditions','Hold only a single company''s stock for maximum focus']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'An index fund aims to match, not beat, the returns of a market index by holding its components, which keeps costs low.','An index fund aims to match, not beat, the returns of a market index by holding its components, which keeps costs low.','An index fund passively holds the securities in a target index, such as a broad stock market index, rather than trying to outsmart the market. Because it requires little active management, it typically charges very low fees, which directly improves long-term net returns. This combination of instant diversification and low cost is why index funds are a popular core holding for long-term investors.','An index fund passively holds the securities in a target index, such as a broad stock market index, rather than trying to outsmart the market. Because it requires little active management, it typically charges very low fees, which directly improves long-term net returns. This combination of instant diversification and low cost is why index funds are a popular core holding for long-term investors.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-investing-3','finance','finance:investing','finance-investing-3','advanced','mcq','Why does compound growth tend to favor investors who start early, even with smaller contributions?','Why does compound growth tend to favor investors who start early, even with smaller contributions?',ARRAY['Earnings are reinvested and themselves generate earnings over a longer time horizon','Starting early guarantees a higher interest rate than starting later','Early investments are exempt from any market losses','Compounding only applies to money invested before a certain age']::text[],ARRAY['Earnings are reinvested and themselves generate earnings over a longer time horizon','Starting early guarantees a higher interest rate than starting later','Early investments are exempt from any market losses','Compounding only applies to money invested before a certain age']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Compounding reinvests returns so they generate further returns, and a longer time horizon gives that snowball effect far more time to grow.','Compounding reinvests returns so they generate further returns, and a longer time horizon gives that snowball effect far more time to grow.','Compound growth means the returns you earn are reinvested and go on to earn returns of their own. The longer your money stays invested, the more dramatic this snowball becomes, so time in the market is often more powerful than the amount invested. This is why a modest sum invested in your twenties can outgrow a larger sum invested decades later.','Compound growth means the returns you earn are reinvested and go on to earn returns of their own. The longer your money stays invested, the more dramatic this snowball becomes, so time in the market is often more powerful than the amount invested. This is why a modest sum invested in your twenties can outgrow a larger sum invested decades later.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-retirement-1','finance','finance:retirement','finance-retirement-1','beginner','mcq','What is the main advantage of a tax-advantaged retirement account compared with an ordinary taxable account?','What is the main advantage of a tax-advantaged retirement account compared with an ordinary taxable account?',ARRAY['It offers tax benefits designed to encourage long-term retirement saving','It guarantees your investments can never lose value','It lets you withdraw money any time with no rules at all','It pays a fixed government-set interest rate every year']::text[],ARRAY['It offers tax benefits designed to encourage long-term retirement saving','It guarantees your investments can never lose value','It lets you withdraw money any time with no rules at all','It pays a fixed government-set interest rate every year']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Tax-advantaged retirement accounts provide tax breaks, such as deferred or tax-free growth, to reward saving for retirement.','Tax-advantaged retirement accounts provide tax breaks, such as deferred or tax-free growth, to reward saving for retirement.','Tax-advantaged retirement accounts give you a tax incentive to set money aside for the long term. Depending on the account type, you might get a tax break when you contribute or tax-free withdrawals later, and investments inside the account can grow without yearly tax drag. In exchange for these benefits, the accounts usually have rules and penalties that discourage withdrawing the money before retirement.','Tax-advantaged retirement accounts give you a tax incentive to set money aside for the long term. Depending on the account type, you might get a tax break when you contribute or tax-free withdrawals later, and investments inside the account can grow without yearly tax drag. In exchange for these benefits, the accounts usually have rules and penalties that discourage withdrawing the money before retirement.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-retirement-2','finance','finance:retirement','finance-retirement-2','intermediate','mcq','An employer ''match'' on retirement contributions is best described as what?','An employer ''match'' on retirement contributions is best described as what?',ARRAY['Extra money your employer adds based on what you contribute, up to a limit','A loan from your employer that must be repaid with interest','A tax your employer deducts from your retirement savings','A penalty for contributing too much to your account']::text[],ARRAY['Extra money your employer adds based on what you contribute, up to a limit','A loan from your employer that must be repaid with interest','A tax your employer deducts from your retirement savings','A penalty for contributing too much to your account']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'An employer match is additional money the employer contributes in proportion to your own contributions, effectively an immediate return on your savings.','An employer match is additional money the employer contributes in proportion to your own contributions, effectively an immediate return on your savings.','Many employers offer to match a portion of what you contribute to a workplace retirement plan, up to a set percentage of your pay. This match is essentially free money and an immediate boost to your savings, so contributing at least enough to capture the full match is widely considered a priority. Failing to contribute enough means leaving part of your compensation on the table.','Many employers offer to match a portion of what you contribute to a workplace retirement plan, up to a set percentage of your pay. This match is essentially free money and an immediate boost to your savings, so contributing at least enough to capture the full match is widely considered a priority. Failing to contribute enough means leaving part of your compensation on the table.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-finance-retirement-3','finance','finance:retirement','finance-retirement-3','advanced','mcq','What is the key difference between a traditional (pre-tax) and a Roth (after-tax) retirement account?','What is the key difference between a traditional (pre-tax) and a Roth (after-tax) retirement account?',ARRAY['Traditional contributions may be taxed at withdrawal, while qualified Roth withdrawals are tax-free','Roth contributions are always taxed again when you withdraw them','Traditional accounts can never be invested in stocks','Roth accounts require you to pay tax on growth every year']::text[],ARRAY['Traditional contributions may be taxed at withdrawal, while qualified Roth withdrawals are tax-free','Roth contributions are always taxed again when you withdraw them','Traditional accounts can never be invested in stocks','Roth accounts require you to pay tax on growth every year']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Traditional accounts typically defer tax until withdrawal, whereas Roth accounts are funded with after-tax money and allow qualified withdrawals tax-free.','Traditional accounts typically defer tax until withdrawal, whereas Roth accounts are funded with after-tax money and allow qualified withdrawals tax-free.','The core distinction is when you pay tax. Traditional accounts often let you contribute pre-tax money and defer taxes until you withdraw in retirement, while Roth accounts use money you have already been taxed on so that qualified future withdrawals, including growth, are tax-free. Choosing between them often comes down to whether you expect your tax rate to be higher now or in retirement.','The core distinction is when you pay tax. Traditional accounts often let you contribute pre-tax money and defer taxes until you withdraw in retirement, while Roth accounts use money you have already been taxed on so that qualified future withdrawals, including growth, are tax-free. Choosing between them often comes down to whether you expect your tax rate to be higher now or in retirement.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-averages-1','data','data:averages','data-averages-1','beginner','mcq','A student scores 4, 8, and 9 on three quizzes. What is the mean (average) of these scores?','A student scores 4, 8, and 9 on three quizzes. What is the mean (average) of these scores?',ARRAY['7','8','9','21']::text[],ARRAY['7','8','9','21']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The mean is the sum divided by the count: (4 + 8 + 9) / 3 = 21 / 3 = 7.','The mean is the sum divided by the count: (4 + 8 + 9) / 3 = 21 / 3 = 7.','The mean is found by adding all values together and dividing by how many values there are. It gives a single number that represents the typical size of the values. Because every value contributes to the total, the mean can be pulled up or down by unusually large or small numbers.','The mean is found by adding all values together and dividing by how many values there are. It gives a single number that represents the typical size of the values. Because every value contributes to the total, the mean can be pulled up or down by unusually large or small numbers.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-averages-2','data','data:averages','data-averages-2','intermediate','mcq','Five houses on a street sold for $200k, $210k, $220k, $230k, and $5,000k (a mansion). Which measure best describes a ''typical'' house price on this street?','Five houses on a street sold for $200k, $210k, $220k, $230k, and $5,000k (a mansion). Which measure best describes a ''typical'' house price on this street?',ARRAY['The median, because it is not distorted by the one extreme value','The mean, because it uses every value','The range, because it shows the full spread','The mode, because prices repeat']::text[],ARRAY['The median, because it is not distorted by the one extreme value','The mean, because it uses every value','The range, because it shows the full spread','The mode, because prices repeat']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The single $5,000k mansion is an outlier that inflates the mean to over $1,000k, while the median of $220k stays close to the cluster of ordinary homes.','The single $5,000k mansion is an outlier that inflates the mean to over $1,000k, while the median of $220k stays close to the cluster of ordinary homes.','The median is the middle value when data is sorted in order, so it ignores how far away extreme values are. The mean, by contrast, is sensitive to outliers because every value is added into the total. When data is skewed by a few extreme points, the median usually describes the ''typical'' case more honestly.','The median is the middle value when data is sorted in order, so it ignores how far away extreme values are. The mean, by contrast, is sensitive to outliers because every value is added into the total. When data is skewed by a few extreme points, the median usually describes the ''typical'' case more honestly.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-averages-3','data','data:averages','data-averages-3','advanced','mcq','Two classes both have a mean test score of 70. Class A''s scores are all between 68 and 72, while Class B''s scores range from 40 to 100. Which statement is correct?','Two classes both have a mean test score of 70. Class A''s scores are all between 68 and 72, while Class B''s scores range from 40 to 100. Which statement is correct?',ARRAY['Class B has a larger standard deviation because its scores are more spread out','Class A has a larger standard deviation because it has more students near the mean','Both classes must have the same standard deviation because the means are equal','Standard deviation cannot be compared unless the medians are equal']::text[],ARRAY['Class B has a larger standard deviation because its scores are more spread out','Class A has a larger standard deviation because it has more students near the mean','Both classes must have the same standard deviation because the means are equal','Standard deviation cannot be compared unless the medians are equal']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Standard deviation measures spread around the mean, and Class B''s scores deviate much further from 70 than Class A''s tightly clustered scores, so Class B''s standard deviation is larger.','Standard deviation measures spread around the mean, and Class B''s scores deviate much further from 70 than Class A''s tightly clustered scores, so Class B''s standard deviation is larger.','Standard deviation summarizes how far, on average, values sit from the mean. A small standard deviation means values cluster tightly around the mean; a large one means they are widely scattered. Two data sets can share the same mean yet have very different standard deviations, which is why spread matters as much as the average.','Standard deviation summarizes how far, on average, values sit from the mean. A small standard deviation means values cluster tightly around the mean; a large one means they are widely scattered. Two data sets can share the same mean yet have very different standard deviations, which is why spread matters as much as the average.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-probability-1','data','data:probability','data-probability-1','beginner','mcq','You roll a single fair six-sided die. What is the probability of rolling a 4?','You roll a single fair six-sided die. What is the probability of rolling a 4?',ARRAY['1/6','1/4','4/6','1/2']::text[],ARRAY['1/6','1/4','4/6','1/2']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'There is exactly one face showing a 4 out of six equally likely faces, so the probability is 1/6.','There is exactly one face showing a 4 out of six equally likely faces, so the probability is 1/6.','For equally likely outcomes, probability equals the number of favorable outcomes divided by the total number of outcomes. A fair die has six faces that are all equally likely, so each single value has a probability of one in six. Probabilities always fall between 0 (impossible) and 1 (certain).','For equally likely outcomes, probability equals the number of favorable outcomes divided by the total number of outcomes. A fair die has six faces that are all equally likely, so each single value has a probability of one in six. Probabilities always fall between 0 (impossible) and 1 (certain).',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-probability-2','data','data:probability','data-probability-2','intermediate','mcq','You flip a fair coin twice. What is the probability of getting heads on both flips?','You flip a fair coin twice. What is the probability of getting heads on both flips?',ARRAY['1/4','1/2','2/4 plus 1','3/4']::text[],ARRAY['1/4','1/2','2/4 plus 1','3/4']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The flips are independent, so you multiply the probabilities: (1/2) x (1/2) = 1/4.','The flips are independent, so you multiply the probabilities: (1/2) x (1/2) = 1/4.','When two events are independent, meaning one does not affect the other, the probability that both happen is the product of their individual probabilities. Each coin flip has a 1/2 chance of heads, so two heads in a row is 1/2 times 1/2. Listing all outcomes (HH, HT, TH, TT) confirms that only one of four equally likely results is two heads.','When two events are independent, meaning one does not affect the other, the probability that both happen is the product of their individual probabilities. Each coin flip has a 1/2 chance of heads, so two heads in a row is 1/2 times 1/2. Listing all outcomes (HH, HT, TH, TT) confirms that only one of four equally likely results is two heads.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-probability-3','data','data:probability','data-probability-3','advanced','mcq','A bag has 3 red and 2 blue marbles. You draw two marbles without replacement. What is the probability that both are red?','A bag has 3 red and 2 blue marbles. You draw two marbles without replacement. What is the probability that both are red?',ARRAY['3/10','9/25','3/5','1/2']::text[],ARRAY['3/10','9/25','3/5','1/2']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The first red has probability 3/5; after removing it, the second red has probability 2/4, so (3/5) x (2/4) = 6/20 = 3/10.','The first red has probability 3/5; after removing it, the second red has probability 2/4, so (3/5) x (2/4) = 6/20 = 3/10.','Drawing without replacement makes events dependent, because removing a marble changes what remains for the next draw. You multiply the probability of the first event by the conditional probability of the second given the first. This differs from drawing with replacement, where the counts reset and the draws stay independent.','Drawing without replacement makes events dependent, because removing a marble changes what remains for the next draw. You multiply the probability of the first event by the conditional probability of the second given the first. This differs from drawing with replacement, where the counts reset and the draws stay independent.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-charts-1','data','data:charts','data-charts-1','beginner','mcq','A bar chart shows weekly sales: Monday 10, Tuesday 25, Wednesday 15, and Thursday 30. Which day had the highest sales?','A bar chart shows weekly sales: Monday 10, Tuesday 25, Wednesday 15, and Thursday 30. Which day had the highest sales?',ARRAY['Thursday','Tuesday','Monday','Wednesday']::text[],ARRAY['Thursday','Tuesday','Monday','Wednesday']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Thursday''s value of 30 is larger than 10, 25, and 15, so it has the tallest bar and the highest sales.','Thursday''s value of 30 is larger than 10, 25, and 15, so it has the tallest bar and the highest sales.','In a bar chart, the height (or length) of each bar represents its value, so taller bars mean larger quantities. To compare categories you simply compare bar heights. Bar charts are best for comparing distinct, separate categories rather than showing continuous change over time.','In a bar chart, the height (or length) of each bar represents its value, so taller bars mean larger quantities. To compare categories you simply compare bar heights. Bar charts are best for comparing distinct, separate categories rather than showing continuous change over time.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-charts-2','data','data:charts','data-charts-2','intermediate','mcq','A pie chart of a budget shows Rent at 50%, Food at 25%, and Transport at 25%. If the total monthly budget is $2,000, how much is spent on Food?','A pie chart of a budget shows Rent at 50%, Food at 25%, and Transport at 25%. If the total monthly budget is $2,000, how much is spent on Food?',ARRAY['$500','$1,000','$250','$750']::text[],ARRAY['$500','$1,000','$250','$750']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Food is 25% of the budget, and 25% of $2,000 is 0.25 x 2,000 = $500.','Food is 25% of the budget, and 25% of $2,000 is 0.25 x 2,000 = $500.','A pie chart divides a whole into slices, where each slice''s share of the circle equals its percentage of the total. To find an actual amount, convert the percentage to a decimal and multiply by the whole. Pie charts work well when parts add up to a meaningful 100% but become hard to read with many small slices.','A pie chart divides a whole into slices, where each slice''s share of the circle equals its percentage of the total. To find an actual amount, convert the percentage to a decimal and multiply by the whole. Pie charts work well when parts add up to a meaningful 100% but become hard to read with many small slices.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-charts-3','data','data:charts','data-charts-3','advanced','mcq','A bar chart compares two products. Their actual sales are 100 and 110 units, but the vertical axis starts at 95 instead of 0, making the second bar look about three times taller. Why is this chart misleading?','A bar chart compares two products. Their actual sales are 100 and 110 units, but the vertical axis starts at 95 instead of 0, making the second bar look about three times taller. Why is this chart misleading?',ARRAY['A truncated axis that does not start at zero exaggerates small differences','Bar charts can never be used to compare two products','The bars should be replaced with a pie chart','The difference of 10 units is too large to show accurately']::text[],ARRAY['A truncated axis that does not start at zero exaggerates small differences','Bar charts can never be used to compare two products','The bars should be replaced with a pie chart','The difference of 10 units is too large to show accurately']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Starting the axis at 95 rather than 0 cuts off most of each bar, so a real difference of only 10 units appears visually enormous.','Starting the axis at 95 rather than 0 cuts off most of each bar, so a real difference of only 10 units appears visually enormous.','When a bar chart''s value axis does not begin at zero, the visible bar heights no longer represent the true proportions between values. A small real difference can be stretched to look dramatic, which is a common way charts mislead. A careful reader always checks where the axis starts before trusting how big a difference looks.','When a bar chart''s value axis does not begin at zero, the visible bar heights no longer represent the true proportions between values. A small real difference can be stretched to look dramatic, which is a common way charts mislead. A careful reader always checks where the axis starts before trusting how big a difference looks.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-studies-1','data','data:studies','data-studies-1','beginner','truefalse','True or False: If two things are correlated (they tend to rise and fall together), that proves one of them causes the other.','True or False: If two things are correlated (they tend to rise and fall together), that proves one of them causes the other.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],1,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Correlation alone does not prove causation, because a third factor or pure coincidence could explain why two things move together.','Correlation alone does not prove causation, because a third factor or pure coincidence could explain why two things move together.','Correlation means two variables tend to change together, but it does not reveal why. The link could run in either direction, be caused by a hidden third variable, or be coincidence. Establishing causation usually requires a controlled experiment, not just an observed pattern.','Correlation means two variables tend to change together, but it does not reveal why. The link could run in either direction, be caused by a hidden third variable, or be coincidence. Establishing causation usually requires a controlled experiment, not just an observed pattern.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-studies-2','data','data:studies','data-studies-2','intermediate','mcq','A researcher surveys people leaving a luxury gym about their income and concludes the whole city is wealthy. What is the main flaw in this study?','A researcher surveys people leaving a luxury gym about their income and concludes the whole city is wealthy. What is the main flaw in this study?',ARRAY['The sample is not representative of the whole city','The sample size of a gym is always too small','Income cannot be measured by a survey','Surveys are never valid research tools']::text[],ARRAY['The sample is not representative of the whole city','The sample size of a gym is always too small','Income cannot be measured by a survey','Surveys are never valid research tools']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'People at a luxury gym are not a random cross-section of the city, so the sample is biased toward wealthier residents and cannot represent everyone.','People at a luxury gym are not a random cross-section of the city, so the sample is biased toward wealthier residents and cannot represent everyone.','A study''s conclusions are only as trustworthy as its sample. When the sample is drawn from a group that differs systematically from the whole population, this is called sampling bias. To generalize to a population, you need a sample that is representative, ideally chosen at random.','A study''s conclusions are only as trustworthy as its sample. When the sample is drawn from a group that differs systematically from the whole population, this is called sampling bias. To generalize to a population, you need a sample that is representative, ideally chosen at random.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-data-studies-3','data','data:studies','data-studies-3','advanced','mcq','A study finds towns with more ice cream sales also have more drownings, and concludes ice cream causes drowning. What is the most likely real explanation?','A study finds towns with more ice cream sales also have more drownings, and concludes ice cream causes drowning. What is the most likely real explanation?',ARRAY['Hot summer weather is a confounding variable that increases both ice cream sales and swimming','Ice cream genuinely makes people more likely to drown','Drowning makes people crave ice cream','The two variables are completely unrelated by chance alone']::text[],ARRAY['Hot summer weather is a confounding variable that increases both ice cream sales and swimming','Ice cream genuinely makes people more likely to drown','Drowning makes people crave ice cream','The two variables are completely unrelated by chance alone']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Warm weather independently drives both more ice cream purchases and more swimming (and thus drownings), creating a correlation without any direct causal link between the two.','Warm weather independently drives both more ice cream purchases and more swimming (and thus drownings), creating a correlation without any direct causal link between the two.','A confounding variable is a hidden third factor that influences both of the variables you are comparing, creating a misleading correlation between them. Failing to account for confounders is a classic source of false causal claims. Good studies try to control for or randomize away such hidden factors so the true relationship can be seen.','A confounding variable is a hidden third factor that influences both of the variables you are comparing, creating a misleading correlation between them. Failing to account for confounders is a classic source of false causal claims. Good studies try to control for or randomize away such hidden factors so the true relationship can be seen.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-listening-1','interpersonal','interpersonal:listening','interpersonal-listening-1','beginner','mcq','A coworker is explaining a problem they ran into. Which behavior best shows you are actively listening?','A coworker is explaining a problem they ran into. Which behavior best shows you are actively listening?',ARRAY['Paraphrasing what they said back to them to confirm you understood','Thinking about how you''ll respond while they are still talking','Checking your phone but nodding occasionally','Jumping in to solve the problem before they finish']::text[],ARRAY['Paraphrasing what they said back to them to confirm you understood','Thinking about how you''ll respond while they are still talking','Checking your phone but nodding occasionally','Jumping in to solve the problem before they finish']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Paraphrasing the speaker''s point back to them confirms understanding and signals that you were genuinely attending to their words.','Paraphrasing the speaker''s point back to them confirms understanding and signals that you were genuinely attending to their words.','Active listening means fully concentrating on the speaker rather than passively hearing them. A core technique is reflecting or paraphrasing what you heard, which both checks your understanding and shows the speaker they were heard. This builds trust and reduces miscommunication.','Active listening means fully concentrating on the speaker rather than passively hearing them. A core technique is reflecting or paraphrasing what you heard, which both checks your understanding and shows the speaker they were heard. This builds trust and reduces miscommunication.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-listening-2','interpersonal','interpersonal:listening','interpersonal-listening-2','intermediate','mcq','During a one-on-one, a teammate says, ''I guess the project went fine,'' but sounds flat and hesitant. What is the best active-listening response?','During a one-on-one, a teammate says, ''I guess the project went fine,'' but sounds flat and hesitant. What is the best active-listening response?',ARRAY['Reflect what you notice: ''You say it went fine, but you sound unsure. What''s on your mind?''','Take them at their word and move to the next agenda item','Reassure them: ''I''m sure it was great, don''t worry about it.''','Point out that they should sound more confident in meetings']::text[],ARRAY['Reflect what you notice: ''You say it went fine, but you sound unsure. What''s on your mind?''','Take them at their word and move to the next agenda item','Reassure them: ''I''m sure it was great, don''t worry about it.''','Point out that they should sound more confident in meetings']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Naming the mismatch between their words and tone invites them to share what they actually feel, which is the goal of listening for meaning beneath the words.','Naming the mismatch between their words and tone invites them to share what they actually feel, which is the goal of listening for meaning beneath the words.','Skilled listeners attend to nonverbal cues like tone, pace, and hesitation, not just the literal words. When words and signals conflict, gently reflecting the discrepancy opens space for the real message. This is sometimes called listening for the music behind the words.','Skilled listeners attend to nonverbal cues like tone, pace, and hesitation, not just the literal words. When words and signals conflict, gently reflecting the discrepancy opens space for the real message. This is sometimes called listening for the music behind the words.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-listening-3','interpersonal','interpersonal:listening','interpersonal-listening-3','advanced','truefalse','True or False: Asking clarifying, open-ended questions can be a form of active listening, even though you are the one speaking.','True or False: Asking clarifying, open-ended questions can be a form of active listening, even though you are the one speaking.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Open-ended questions that draw out and deepen the speaker''s meaning are a recognized active-listening skill, because their purpose is to understand rather than to redirect.','Open-ended questions that draw out and deepen the speaker''s meaning are a recognized active-listening skill, because their purpose is to understand rather than to redirect.','Active listening is not silent passivity; it includes verbal techniques that serve understanding. Open-ended questions such as ''What led you to that?'' encourage the speaker to elaborate and show you are tracking their thinking. The test is intent: questions that explore the speaker''s view aid listening, while questions that steer toward your own agenda do not.','Active listening is not silent passivity; it includes verbal techniques that serve understanding. Open-ended questions such as ''What led you to that?'' encourage the speaker to elaborate and show you are tracking their thinking. The test is intent: questions that explore the speaker''s view aid listening, while questions that steer toward your own agenda do not.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-feedback-1','interpersonal','interpersonal:feedback','interpersonal-feedback-1','beginner','mcq','Which of these is the most effective feedback to give a colleague?','Which of these is the most effective feedback to give a colleague?',ARRAY['''In yesterday''s review, you interrupted Maria twice before she finished her point.''','''You''re kind of rude in meetings.''','''Everyone thinks you talk over people.''','''You always make meetings difficult.''']::text[],ARRAY['''In yesterday''s review, you interrupted Maria twice before she finished her point.''','''You''re kind of rude in meetings.''','''Everyone thinks you talk over people.''','''You always make meetings difficult.''']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Effective feedback describes a specific, observable behavior at a specific time, rather than labeling the person''s character.','Effective feedback describes a specific, observable behavior at a specific time, rather than labeling the person''s character.','Good feedback is specific and behavior-focused, pointing to what someone actually did rather than judging who they are. Vague or character-based labels like ''rude'' put people on the defensive and give them nothing concrete to change. Naming the exact behavior makes the feedback both fair and actionable.','Good feedback is specific and behavior-focused, pointing to what someone actually did rather than judging who they are. Vague or character-based labels like ''rude'' put people on the defensive and give them nothing concrete to change. Naming the exact behavior makes the feedback both fair and actionable.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-feedback-2','interpersonal','interpersonal:feedback','interpersonal-feedback-2','intermediate','mcq','You want to tell a teammate that their late report delayed your work. Which phrasing is most constructive?','You want to tell a teammate that their late report delayed your work. Which phrasing is most constructive?',ARRAY['''When the report arrived a day late, I had to rush my part and felt stressed.''','''You made me miss my deadline because you''re never on time.''','''Why can''t you ever get things in when you say you will?''','''It''s fine, but try not to be late, I guess.''']::text[],ARRAY['''When the report arrived a day late, I had to rush my part and felt stressed.''','''You made me miss my deadline because you''re never on time.''','''Why can''t you ever get things in when you say you will?''','''It''s fine, but try not to be late, I guess.''']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'An ''I'' statement that links a specific behavior to its concrete impact and your own experience delivers the message without attacking the person.','An ''I'' statement that links a specific behavior to its concrete impact and your own experience delivers the message without attacking the person.','''I'' statements describe the situation, the effect on you, and how you felt, instead of accusing the other person with ''you'' blame. The structure ''When X happened, I experienced Y'' keeps the focus on impact rather than character. This lowers defensiveness and makes the listener more able to hear and act on the feedback.','''I'' statements describe the situation, the effect on you, and how you felt, instead of accusing the other person with ''you'' blame. The structure ''When X happened, I experienced Y'' keeps the focus on impact rather than character. This lowers defensiveness and makes the listener more able to hear and act on the feedback.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-feedback-3','interpersonal','interpersonal:feedback','interpersonal-feedback-3','advanced','mcq','A direct report did excellent work but you also need to raise a real concern. What approach makes the feedback most credible?','A direct report did excellent work but you also need to raise a real concern. What approach makes the feedback most credible?',ARRAY['Give genuine, specific praise and the specific concern as separate, clearly stated messages','Sandwich the criticism between two compliments so it stings less','Skip the praise and lead straight into the criticism to save time','Soften the concern so much that it sounds optional']::text[],ARRAY['Give genuine, specific praise and the specific concern as separate, clearly stated messages','Sandwich the criticism between two compliments so it stings less','Skip the praise and lead straight into the criticism to save time','Soften the concern so much that it sounds optional']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Keeping praise and concern specific and distinct preserves the credibility of both, whereas burying criticism dilutes the message and can make praise feel manipulative.','Keeping praise and concern specific and distinct preserves the credibility of both, whereas burying criticism dilutes the message and can make praise feel manipulative.','The classic ''feedback sandwich'' often backfires because people learn to discount the praise as mere padding for bad news. Research and practice favor being clear and specific about both strengths and concerns, treating each as a real, standalone message. Honesty paired with specificity earns trust; manufactured softening erodes it.','The classic ''feedback sandwich'' often backfires because people learn to discount the praise as mere padding for bad news. Research and practice favor being clear and specific about both strengths and concerns, treating each as a real, standalone message. Honesty paired with specificity earns trust; manufactured softening erodes it.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-negotiation-1','interpersonal','interpersonal:negotiation','interpersonal-negotiation-1','beginner','mcq','In a negotiation, what does it mean to focus on ''interests'' rather than ''positions''?','In a negotiation, what does it mean to focus on ''interests'' rather than ''positions''?',ARRAY['Looking at the underlying needs behind what each side is demanding','Sticking firmly to your opening demand no matter what','Caring only about the other side''s stated final offer','Splitting the difference as quickly as possible']::text[],ARRAY['Looking at the underlying needs behind what each side is demanding','Sticking firmly to your opening demand no matter what','Caring only about the other side''s stated final offer','Splitting the difference as quickly as possible']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Interests are the underlying needs and motivations driving a demand, and focusing on them opens up solutions a rigid position would hide.','Interests are the underlying needs and motivations driving a demand, and focusing on them opens up solutions a rigid position would hide.','A position is what someone says they want; an interest is why they want it. Two people arguing over a single orange may both get more if one needs the peel and the other the fruit. Identifying interests behind positions is a foundation of principled negotiation because it reveals options that satisfy both sides.','A position is what someone says they want; an interest is why they want it. Two people arguing over a single orange may both get more if one needs the peel and the other the fruit. Identifying interests behind positions is a foundation of principled negotiation because it reveals options that satisfy both sides.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-negotiation-2','interpersonal','interpersonal:negotiation','interpersonal-negotiation-2','intermediate','mcq','You are negotiating a contract. What does knowing your BATNA give you?','You are negotiating a contract. What does knowing your BATNA give you?',ARRAY['A clear sense of your best alternative if no deal is reached, so you know when to walk away','A guarantee that the other side will accept your first offer','Permission to ignore the other party''s interests entirely','A rule that you must always accept any offer above your asking price']::text[],ARRAY['A clear sense of your best alternative if no deal is reached, so you know when to walk away','A guarantee that the other side will accept your first offer','Permission to ignore the other party''s interests entirely','A rule that you must always accept any offer above your asking price']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'BATNA stands for Best Alternative To a Negotiated Agreement, and knowing it tells you the point at which walking away beats accepting a poor deal.','BATNA stands for Best Alternative To a Negotiated Agreement, and knowing it tells you the point at which walking away beats accepting a poor deal.','Your BATNA is what you will do if this particular negotiation fails. It sets your walk-away point: you should not accept any deal worse than your best alternative. A strong, well-understood BATNA increases your leverage and protects you from being pressured into an agreement that leaves you worse off.','Your BATNA is what you will do if this particular negotiation fails. It sets your walk-away point: you should not accept any deal worse than your best alternative. A strong, well-understood BATNA increases your leverage and protects you from being pressured into an agreement that leaves you worse off.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-negotiation-3','interpersonal','interpersonal:negotiation','interpersonal-negotiation-3','advanced','mcq','The other party opens with an aggressive, extreme number. What is the most effective response?','The other party opens with an aggressive, extreme number. What is the most effective response?',ARRAY['Avoid anchoring to it, refocus on objective criteria, and ask how they arrived at that figure','Immediately counter with an equally extreme number in the opposite direction','Accept a small concession from their number to keep things friendly','Walk out of the negotiation in protest of the tactic']::text[],ARRAY['Avoid anchoring to it, refocus on objective criteria, and ask how they arrived at that figure','Immediately counter with an equally extreme number in the opposite direction','Accept a small concession from their number to keep things friendly','Walk out of the negotiation in protest of the tactic']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Declining to treat the extreme figure as a reference point and steering toward objective standards neutralizes the anchor without escalating or conceding.','Declining to treat the extreme figure as a reference point and steering toward objective standards neutralizes the anchor without escalating or conceding.','An aggressive first offer is an anchoring tactic, exploiting our tendency to judge value relative to the first number we hear. The countermeasure is to refuse the anchor''s pull and insist on independent, objective criteria such as market rates or precedent. Asking the other side to justify their number also exposes weak reasoning and resets the conversation onto fairer ground.','An aggressive first offer is an anchoring tactic, exploiting our tendency to judge value relative to the first number we hear. The countermeasure is to refuse the anchor''s pull and insist on independent, objective criteria such as market rates or precedent. Asking the other side to justify their number also exposes weak reasoning and resets the conversation onto fairer ground.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-conflict-1','interpersonal','interpersonal:conflict','interpersonal-conflict-1','beginner','mcq','A friend is visibly upset and venting about a hard day. What is the most empathetic first response?','A friend is visibly upset and venting about a hard day. What is the most empathetic first response?',ARRAY['''That sounds really frustrating. What happened?''','''Well, at least it wasn''t worse than my day.''','''You should just stop letting it bother you.''','''Here''s exactly what you need to do to fix it.''']::text[],ARRAY['''That sounds really frustrating. What happened?''','''Well, at least it wasn''t worse than my day.''','''You should just stop letting it bother you.''','''Here''s exactly what you need to do to fix it.''']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Acknowledging the person''s emotion and inviting them to say more shows empathy before any attempt to fix or compare.','Acknowledging the person''s emotion and inviting them to say more shows empathy before any attempt to fix or compare.','Empathy starts with recognizing and validating another person''s feelings rather than minimizing, comparing, or rushing to solutions. Acknowledging emotion first signals that the person matters and makes them feel understood. Only once someone feels heard are they usually ready to think about solutions.','Empathy starts with recognizing and validating another person''s feelings rather than minimizing, comparing, or rushing to solutions. Acknowledging emotion first signals that the person matters and makes them feel understood. Only once someone feels heard are they usually ready to think about solutions.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-conflict-2','interpersonal','interpersonal:conflict','interpersonal-conflict-2','intermediate','truefalse','True or False: When someone comes to you angry about a problem, acknowledging their emotion before jumping to solutions usually makes the conversation go better.','True or False: When someone comes to you angry about a problem, acknowledging their emotion before jumping to solutions usually makes the conversation go better.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Acknowledging the emotion first helps the person feel heard and calms the interaction, making them more open to problem-solving afterward.','Acknowledging the emotion first helps the person feel heard and calms the interaction, making them more open to problem-solving afterward.','Strong emotion narrows people''s capacity to reason and absorb solutions. Naming and validating the feeling, sometimes called affect labeling, helps reduce its intensity and signals respect. Once the person feels understood, the conversation can shift productively to addressing the underlying problem.','Strong emotion narrows people''s capacity to reason and absorb solutions. Naming and validating the feeling, sometimes called affect labeling, helps reduce its intensity and signals respect. Once the person feels understood, the conversation can shift productively to addressing the underlying problem.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-interpersonal-conflict-3','interpersonal','interpersonal:conflict','interpersonal-conflict-3','advanced','mcq','Two team members are in a heated disagreement and each insists the other is wrong. As a neutral colleague, what is the most effective way to de-escalate?','Two team members are in a heated disagreement and each insists the other is wrong. As a neutral colleague, what is the most effective way to de-escalate?',ARRAY['Have each person restate the other''s view to the other''s satisfaction before debating solutions','Decide who is right based on who argues more forcefully','Tell them both to drop it and move on for now','Take the side of whoever you personally agree with']::text[],ARRAY['Have each person restate the other''s view to the other''s satisfaction before debating solutions','Decide who is right based on who argues more forcefully','Tell them both to drop it and move on for now','Take the side of whoever you personally agree with']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Requiring each person to accurately restate the other''s view ensures both feel understood and surfaces the real disagreement, which lowers defensiveness before solving the problem.','Requiring each person to accurately restate the other''s view ensures both feel understood and surfaces the real disagreement, which lowers defensiveness before solving the problem.','In heated conflict, people dig in partly because they feel unheard. A powerful de-escalation technique is to have each side reflect the other''s position until that person agrees it was captured fairly. This forces genuine perspective-taking, separates real disagreements from misunderstandings, and replaces a contest of wills with mutual understanding.','In heated conflict, people dig in partly because they feel unheard. A powerful de-escalation technique is to have each side reflect the other''s position until that person agrees it was captured fairly. This forces genuine perspective-taking, separates real disagreements from misunderstandings, and replaces a contest of wills with mutual understanding.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-structure-1','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-1','beginner','mcq','You have ten minutes to give a talk on switching to a four-day work week. Which overall structure will be clearest for your audience?','You have ten minutes to give a talk on switching to a four-day work week. Which overall structure will be clearest for your audience?',ARRAY['Open by previewing your main points, deliver them in order, then summarize what you covered','List every fact you know in the order you happened to learn them','Start with your conclusion, then read your reference list aloud','Improvise freely and trust the audience to find the thread']::text[],ARRAY['Open by previewing your main points, deliver them in order, then summarize what you covered','List every fact you know in the order you happened to learn them','Start with your conclusion, then read your reference list aloud','Improvise freely and trust the audience to find the thread']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Telling the audience what you''ll cover, covering it, then recapping gives listeners a roadmap that makes the content easy to follow and remember.','Telling the audience what you''ll cover, covering it, then recapping gives listeners a roadmap that makes the content easy to follow and remember.','A classic talk structure has a clear beginning, middle, and end: preview your key points, develop them one at a time, then summarize. Listeners cannot rewind a live talk, so this repetition helps them follow and retain the message. The structure also keeps you on track and prevents rambling.','A classic talk structure has a clear beginning, middle, and end: preview your key points, develop them one at a time, then summarize. Listeners cannot rewind a live talk, so this repetition helps them follow and retain the message. The structure also keeps you on track and prevents rambling.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-structure-2','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-2','intermediate','mcq','Midway through a presentation you want listeners to clearly notice that you are moving from describing a problem to proposing solutions. What is the most effective technique?','Midway through a presentation you want listeners to clearly notice that you are moving from describing a problem to proposing solutions. What is the most effective technique?',ARRAY['Use a verbal signpost such as ''Now that we''ve seen the problem, let''s look at three ways to fix it''','Lower your voice and hope people infer the shift','Add a new slide with no spoken transition','Speed up so you can reach the solutions faster']::text[],ARRAY['Use a verbal signpost such as ''Now that we''ve seen the problem, let''s look at three ways to fix it''','Lower your voice and hope people infer the shift','Add a new slide with no spoken transition','Speed up so you can reach the solutions faster']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'An explicit signpost tells the audience where you are in the talk and what is coming next, keeping them oriented through the transition.','An explicit signpost tells the audience where you are in the talk and what is coming next, keeping them oriented through the transition.','Signposting uses transition phrases like ''first'', ''on the other hand'', and ''to sum up'' to mark the boundaries between sections of a talk. Because audiences cannot see your outline, these verbal cues act as a map that keeps them from getting lost. Strong transitions also make the talk feel deliberate and well organized rather than a loose collection of points.','Signposting uses transition phrases like ''first'', ''on the other hand'', and ''to sum up'' to mark the boundaries between sections of a talk. Because audiences cannot see your outline, these verbal cues act as a map that keeps them from getting lost. Strong transitions also make the talk feel deliberate and well organized rather than a loose collection of points.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-structure-3','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-3','advanced','mcq','You want your closing line to feel memorable and complete. Which approach best creates that sense of resolution?','You want your closing line to feel memorable and complete. Which approach best creates that sense of resolution?',ARRAY['Call back to the story or image you opened with, tying the ending to the beginning','End abruptly with ''Well, that''s all I have, I guess''','Introduce a brand-new statistic the audience hasn''t heard before','Apologize for running over time and rush off']::text[],ARRAY['Call back to the story or image you opened with, tying the ending to the beginning','End abruptly with ''Well, that''s all I have, I guess''','Introduce a brand-new statistic the audience hasn''t heard before','Apologize for running over time and rush off']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Returning to the opening image or story creates a ''bookend'' that gives the talk a satisfying, deliberate sense of closure.','Returning to the opening image or story creates a ''bookend'' that gives the talk a satisfying, deliberate sense of closure.','The callback or ''bookending'' technique frames a talk by echoing its opening at the close, signaling to the audience that the journey is complete. This narrative symmetry feels intentional and resolves the tension or curiosity raised at the start. Avoid ending with new information or weak filler, which leave listeners feeling the talk simply trailed off.','The callback or ''bookending'' technique frames a talk by echoing its opening at the close, signaling to the audience that the journey is complete. This narrative symmetry feels intentional and resolves the tension or curiosity raised at the start. Avoid ending with new information or weak filler, which leave listeners feeling the talk simply trailed off.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-delivery-1','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-1','beginner','truefalse','Pausing briefly after an important point gives the audience time to absorb it and can make the point land harder.','Pausing briefly after an important point gives the audience time to absorb it and can make the point land harder.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A deliberate pause lets a key idea sink in and adds emphasis, which is why experienced speakers pause rather than rush onward.','A deliberate pause lets a key idea sink in and adds emphasis, which is why experienced speakers pause rather than rush onward.','Pauses are one of the most powerful tools in delivery: they give listeners a moment to process what you just said and they spotlight the words around them. Silence also lets you breathe and reset your pace. New speakers often fear pauses and fill them with ''um'' or rush ahead, but a confident pause reads as poise, not hesitation.','Pauses are one of the most powerful tools in delivery: they give listeners a moment to process what you just said and they spotlight the words around them. Silence also lets you breathe and reset your pace. New speakers often fear pauses and fill them with ''um'' or rush ahead, but a confident pause reads as poise, not hesitation.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-delivery-2','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-2','intermediate','mcq','You notice you race through talks and listeners look lost. Which adjustment will most improve how easily people follow you?','You notice you race through talks and listeners look lost. Which adjustment will most improve how easily people follow you?',ARRAY['Slow your overall pace and add short pauses at the end of key sentences','Speak in a flat monotone so every word gets equal weight','Talk even faster to fit more detail into the time','Memorize the script word for word and recite it quickly']::text[],ARRAY['Slow your overall pace and add short pauses at the end of key sentences','Speak in a flat monotone so every word gets equal weight','Talk even faster to fit more detail into the time','Memorize the script word for word and recite it quickly']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Slowing down and pausing at sentence ends gives listeners time to process each idea, which is the core fix for a too-fast delivery.','Slowing down and pausing at sentence ends gives listeners time to process each idea, which is the core fix for a too-fast delivery.','Pacing is how fast you speak and where you pause, and a measured pace dramatically improves comprehension. Nervous speakers tend to accelerate, blurring their words together so the audience can''t keep up. Deliberately slowing down, varying your speed, and pausing at natural breaks gives ideas room to breathe and makes you sound more confident.','Pacing is how fast you speak and where you pause, and a measured pace dramatically improves comprehension. Nervous speakers tend to accelerate, blurring their words together so the audience can''t keep up. Deliberately slowing down, varying your speed, and pausing at natural breaks gives ideas room to breathe and makes you sound more confident.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-delivery-3','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-3','advanced','mcq','Throughout a talk your voice stays at one steady pitch and volume. Why does adding vocal variety make you a more effective speaker?','Throughout a talk your voice stays at one steady pitch and volume. Why does adding vocal variety make you a more effective speaker?',ARRAY['Changing pitch, pace, and volume signals emphasis and emotion, keeping the audience engaged and highlighting what matters','It makes the talk longer, which audiences always prefer','A monotone is actually ideal because it sounds calm and authoritative','Volume changes only matter for singers, not speakers']::text[],ARRAY['Changing pitch, pace, and volume signals emphasis and emotion, keeping the audience engaged and highlighting what matters','It makes the talk longer, which audiences always prefer','A monotone is actually ideal because it sounds calm and authoritative','Volume changes only matter for singers, not speakers']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Varying pitch, pace, and volume marks which words carry weight and conveys feeling, preventing the monotony that makes listeners tune out.','Varying pitch, pace, and volume marks which words carry weight and conveys feeling, preventing the monotony that makes listeners tune out.','Vocal variety, the modulation of pitch, pace, and volume, is what keeps a voice engaging and meaningful. A monotone delivery flattens emphasis so the audience can''t tell what is important and quickly loses attention. Strategic changes, like dropping your volume for an intimate point or raising pitch for excitement, guide listeners'' emotions and underline your key ideas.','Vocal variety, the modulation of pitch, pace, and volume, is what keeps a voice engaging and meaningful. A monotone delivery flattens emphasis so the audience can''t tell what is important and quickly loses attention. Strategic changes, like dropping your volume for an intimate point or raising pitch for excitement, guide listeners'' emotions and underline your key ideas.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-nerves-1','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-1','beginner','mcq','Just before you walk on stage your heart is pounding and your breathing is shallow. What is a quick, proven way to calm yourself in the moment?','Just before you walk on stage your heart is pounding and your breathing is shallow. What is a quick, proven way to calm yourself in the moment?',ARRAY['Take a few slow, deep breaths, exhaling longer than you inhale','Hold your breath until your turn to speak','Drink several cups of strong coffee to feel energized','Replay every way the talk could go wrong']::text[],ARRAY['Take a few slow, deep breaths, exhaling longer than you inhale','Hold your breath until your turn to speak','Drink several cups of strong coffee to feel energized','Replay every way the talk could go wrong']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Slow, deep breathing with a longer exhale activates the body''s calming response and steadies a racing heart before you begin.','Slow, deep breathing with a longer exhale activates the body''s calming response and steadies a racing heart before you begin.','When we feel anxious, breathing becomes fast and shallow, which fuels the body''s stress response. Deliberate slow breathing, especially a long exhale, triggers the parasympathetic nervous system and physically calms you down. A simple round of deep breaths before speaking lowers your heart rate and steadies your voice.','When we feel anxious, breathing becomes fast and shallow, which fuels the body''s stress response. Deliberate slow breathing, especially a long exhale, triggers the parasympathetic nervous system and physically calms you down. A simple round of deep breaths before speaking lowers your heart rate and steadies your voice.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-nerves-2','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-2','intermediate','mcq','A speaker who feels their nerves as ''excitement'' rather than ''fear'' tends to perform better. What is the best explanation for this technique?','A speaker who feels their nerves as ''excitement'' rather than ''fear'' tends to perform better. What is the best explanation for this technique?',ARRAY['Anxiety and excitement feel similar in the body, so relabeling the feeling lets you channel the energy instead of fighting it','It magically removes all physical symptoms of nervousness','Excitement and fear are completely unrelated states','Telling yourself to ''just calm down'' is always more effective']::text[],ARRAY['Anxiety and excitement feel similar in the body, so relabeling the feeling lets you channel the energy instead of fighting it','It magically removes all physical symptoms of nervousness','Excitement and fear are completely unrelated states','Telling yourself to ''just calm down'' is always more effective']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Because the physical arousal of anxiety and excitement is nearly identical, reframing it as excitement is easier than forcing calm and turns the energy to your advantage.','Because the physical arousal of anxiety and excitement is nearly identical, reframing it as excitement is easier than forcing calm and turns the energy to your advantage.','Anxiety reappraisal is the practice of relabeling pre-talk jitters as excitement rather than trying to suppress them. Both states share the same arousal, a racing heart and heightened alertness, so it is easier to shift the label than to switch the body off. Treating the energy as readiness rather than threat helps you channel it into an engaged, lively delivery.','Anxiety reappraisal is the practice of relabeling pre-talk jitters as excitement rather than trying to suppress them. Both states share the same arousal, a racing heart and heightened alertness, so it is easier to shift the label than to switch the body off. Treating the energy as readiness rather than threat helps you channel it into an engaged, lively delivery.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-nerves-3','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-3','advanced','mcq','You want a long-term strategy that reliably reduces stage fright over many talks, not just an in-the-moment trick. What works best?','You want a long-term strategy that reliably reduces stage fright over many talks, not just an in-the-moment trick. What works best?',ARRAY['Thorough preparation and repeated rehearsal, ideally out loud and under realistic conditions','Avoiding all practice so the talk feels spontaneous','Picturing the audience in their underwear','Waiting until you no longer feel any nerves before agreeing to speak']::text[],ARRAY['Thorough preparation and repeated rehearsal, ideally out loud and under realistic conditions','Avoiding all practice so the talk feels spontaneous','Picturing the audience in their underwear','Waiting until you no longer feel any nerves before agreeing to speak']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Deep preparation and realistic rehearsal build genuine confidence and automaticity, which is the most dependable way to shrink stage fright over time.','Deep preparation and realistic rehearsal build genuine confidence and automaticity, which is the most dependable way to shrink stage fright over time.','Much speaking anxiety comes from fear of the unknown and of forgetting your material. Rehearsing out loud, ideally standing and simulating real conditions, makes the talk familiar so your brain has fewer surprises to dread. Over repeated exposures this preparation builds lasting confidence, whereas gimmicks offer only momentary relief.','Much speaking anxiety comes from fear of the unknown and of forgetting your material. Rehearsing out loud, ideally standing and simulating real conditions, makes the talk familiar so your brain has fewer surprises to dread. Over repeated exposures this preparation builds lasting confidence, whereas gimmicks offer only momentary relief.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-audience-1','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-1','beginner','mcq','You are preparing the same technical update for a room of engineers versus a room of senior executives. What should most shape how you present it?','You are preparing the same technical update for a room of engineers versus a room of senior executives. What should most shape how you present it?',ARRAY['Tailor the depth, jargon, and focus to what each audience already knows and cares about','Deliver the identical slides and wording to both groups','Use as much specialized jargon as possible to sound credible','Decide the content only by what is easiest for you to prepare']::text[],ARRAY['Tailor the depth, jargon, and focus to what each audience already knows and cares about','Deliver the identical slides and wording to both groups','Use as much specialized jargon as possible to sound credible','Decide the content only by what is easiest for you to prepare']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Adapting your depth, vocabulary, and emphasis to each audience''s knowledge and priorities is the foundation of an effective talk.','Adapting your depth, vocabulary, and emphasis to each audience''s knowledge and priorities is the foundation of an effective talk.','Knowing your audience means understanding their existing knowledge, interests, and what they need from you. The same information should be framed differently for specialists than for decision-makers: experts want detail, while executives want implications and outcomes. Matching your message to the listeners makes it relevant and keeps them engaged.','Knowing your audience means understanding their existing knowledge, interests, and what they need from you. The same information should be framed differently for specialists than for decision-makers: experts want detail, while executives want implications and outcomes. Matching your message to the listeners makes it relevant and keeps them engaged.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-audience-2','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-2','intermediate','mcq','During Q&A someone asks a question and you don''t know the answer. What is the most professional response?','During Q&A someone asks a question and you don''t know the answer. What is the most professional response?',ARRAY['Admit you don''t know, then offer to find out and follow up after the session','Make up a confident-sounding answer on the spot','Dismiss the question as irrelevant and move on','Pretend you didn''t hear it and call on someone else']::text[],ARRAY['Admit you don''t know, then offer to find out and follow up after the session','Make up a confident-sounding answer on the spot','Dismiss the question as irrelevant and move on','Pretend you didn''t hear it and call on someone else']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Honestly acknowledging the gap and promising to follow up protects your credibility, whereas bluffing risks being caught in a wrong answer.','Honestly acknowledging the gap and promising to follow up protects your credibility, whereas bluffing risks being caught in a wrong answer.','Audiences trust speakers who are honest about the limits of their knowledge. Saying ''I don''t know, but I''ll find out and get back to you'' is far more credible than inventing an answer that may be wrong. Offering a genuine follow-up turns a tough question into a chance to build trust rather than lose it.','Audiences trust speakers who are honest about the limits of their knowledge. Saying ''I don''t know, but I''ll find out and get back to you'' is far more credible than inventing an answer that may be wrong. Offering a genuine follow-up turns a tough question into a chance to build trust rather than lose it.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-audience-3','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-3','advanced','mcq','In Q&A a hostile audience member asks a loaded, off-topic question meant to derail you. Which technique lets you stay composed and steer back to your message?','In Q&A a hostile audience member asks a loaded, off-topic question meant to derail you. Which technique lets you stay composed and steer back to your message?',ARRAY['Briefly acknowledge the question, then bridge to a relevant key point with a phrase like ''What''s important here is...''','Argue with the questioner point by point until one of you gives up','Ignore them completely and refuse to respond at all','Abandon your message and let them set the agenda']::text[],ARRAY['Briefly acknowledge the question, then bridge to a relevant key point with a phrase like ''What''s important here is...''','Argue with the questioner point by point until one of you gives up','Ignore them completely and refuse to respond at all','Abandon your message and let them set the agenda']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Bridging acknowledges the question without taking the bait, then transitions to a point you want to make, keeping you in control of the conversation.','Bridging acknowledges the question without taking the bait, then transitions to a point you want to make, keeping you in control of the conversation.','Bridging is a technique borrowed from media training for handling difficult or off-topic questions. You give a brief, respectful acknowledgment, then use a transition phrase to pivot to one of your core messages. This keeps you calm and in control, addresses the moment without getting trapped in a hostile tangent, and returns focus to what you came to say.','Bridging is a technique borrowed from media training for handling difficult or off-topic questions. You give a brief, respectful acknowledgment, then use a transition phrase to pivot to one of your core messages. This keeps you calm and in control, addresses the moment without getting trapped in a hostile tangent, and returns focus to what you came to say.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-ml-1','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-1','beginner','mcq','A model is trained on emails that are each already labeled as ''spam'' or ''not spam'' so it can label new emails. What type of machine learning is this?','A model is trained on emails that are each already labeled as ''spam'' or ''not spam'' so it can label new emails. What type of machine learning is this?',ARRAY['Supervised learning','Unsupervised learning','Reinforcement learning','Clustering']::text[],ARRAY['Supervised learning','Unsupervised learning','Reinforcement learning','Clustering']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Learning from input examples paired with known correct labels is the defining characteristic of supervised learning.','Learning from input examples paired with known correct labels is the defining characteristic of supervised learning.','Supervised learning trains a model on data where each example has a known target answer, so the model learns to map inputs to those labels. Once trained, it predicts labels for new, unseen inputs. Common tasks include classification (predicting categories) and regression (predicting numbers).','Supervised learning trains a model on data where each example has a known target answer, so the model learns to map inputs to those labels. Once trained, it predicts labels for new, unseen inputs. Common tasks include classification (predicting categories) and regression (predicting numbers).',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-ml-2','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-2','intermediate','mcq','You have a dataset of customer purchases with no labels, and you want to discover natural groupings of similar customers. Which approach fits best?','You have a dataset of customer purchases with no labels, and you want to discover natural groupings of similar customers. Which approach fits best?',ARRAY['Clustering, an unsupervised method','Linear regression, a supervised method','Logistic regression, a supervised method','A labeled train-test split']::text[],ARRAY['Clustering, an unsupervised method','Linear regression, a supervised method','Logistic regression, a supervised method','A labeled train-test split']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Finding groupings in unlabeled data without predefined categories is unsupervised learning, and clustering is its canonical technique.','Finding groupings in unlabeled data without predefined categories is unsupervised learning, and clustering is its canonical technique.','Unsupervised learning works with data that has no target labels, aiming to uncover hidden structure. Clustering groups similar examples together, while other unsupervised methods reduce dimensionality or detect anomalies. Because there are no ground-truth answers, results are evaluated by how meaningful or useful the discovered structure is.','Unsupervised learning works with data that has no target labels, aiming to uncover hidden structure. Clustering groups similar examples together, while other unsupervised methods reduce dimensionality or detect anomalies. Because there are no ground-truth answers, results are evaluated by how meaningful or useful the discovered structure is.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-ml-3','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-3','advanced','mcq','A model reaches 99% accuracy on its training data but only 70% on a held-out test set. What is the most likely problem and a reasonable fix?','A model reaches 99% accuracy on its training data but only 70% on a held-out test set. What is the most likely problem and a reasonable fix?',ARRAY['Overfitting; add regularization or more training data','Underfitting; make the model much larger','The test set is too easy; remove it','Data leakage; raise the learning rate']::text[],ARRAY['Overfitting; add regularization or more training data','Underfitting; make the model much larger','The test set is too easy; remove it','Data leakage; raise the learning rate']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A large gap between high training accuracy and lower test accuracy signals overfitting, which regularization or more diverse data helps reduce.','A large gap between high training accuracy and lower test accuracy signals overfitting, which regularization or more diverse data helps reduce.','Overfitting happens when a model memorizes quirks and noise in the training data instead of learning patterns that generalize. The telltale sign is strong training performance paired with weak performance on new data. Remedies include regularization, gathering more or more varied data, simplifying the model, and early stopping during training.','Overfitting happens when a model memorizes quirks and noise in the training data instead of learning patterns that generalize. The telltale sign is strong training performance paired with weak performance on new data. Remedies include regularization, gathering more or more varied data, simplifying the model, and early stopping during training.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-neural-1','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-1','beginner','truefalse','Without a non-linear activation function, a stack of neural network layers can only represent linear relationships between inputs and outputs.','Without a non-linear activation function, a stack of neural network layers can only represent linear relationships between inputs and outputs.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Composing purely linear layers still yields a single linear function, so non-linear activations are what let networks model complex patterns.','Composing purely linear layers still yields a single linear function, so non-linear activations are what let networks model complex patterns.','Each layer of a neural network typically computes a weighted sum followed by an activation function. If the activation were linear (or absent), stacking layers would collapse into one equivalent linear transformation, limiting the network to straight-line relationships. Non-linear activations like ReLU, sigmoid, or tanh break this collapse, enabling networks to approximate complex, curved decision boundaries.','Each layer of a neural network typically computes a weighted sum followed by an activation function. If the activation were linear (or absent), stacking layers would collapse into one equivalent linear transformation, limiting the network to straight-line relationships. Non-linear activations like ReLU, sigmoid, or tanh break this collapse, enabling networks to approximate complex, curved decision boundaries.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-neural-2','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-2','intermediate','mcq','In gradient descent, what role does the gradient of the loss function play during a training step?','In gradient descent, what role does the gradient of the loss function play during a training step?',ARRAY['It points in the direction of steepest increase, so we step opposite to it to reduce loss','It directly sets the final weight values in one step','It measures how accurate the model is on the test set','It randomly shuffles the training data between epochs']::text[],ARRAY['It points in the direction of steepest increase, so we step opposite to it to reduce loss','It directly sets the final weight values in one step','It measures how accurate the model is on the test set','It randomly shuffles the training data between epochs']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The gradient indicates the direction of steepest loss increase, so updating weights in the opposite direction lowers the loss.','The gradient indicates the direction of steepest loss increase, so updating weights in the opposite direction lowers the loss.','Gradient descent improves a model by repeatedly nudging its weights to reduce a loss that measures error. The gradient is the vector of partial derivatives showing how the loss changes with each weight; it points uphill, so we move against it. The learning rate controls how big each step is, balancing speed against the risk of overshooting.','Gradient descent improves a model by repeatedly nudging its weights to reduce a loss that measures error. The gradient is the vector of partial derivatives showing how the loss changes with each weight; it points uphill, so we move against it. The learning rate controls how big each step is, balancing speed against the risk of overshooting.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-neural-3','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-3','advanced','mcq','What is the core purpose of the backpropagation algorithm in training a neural network?','What is the core purpose of the backpropagation algorithm in training a neural network?',ARRAY['To efficiently compute the gradient of the loss with respect to every weight using the chain rule','To choose the best activation function for each layer automatically','To split the dataset into training and test sets','To increase the learning rate when training slows down']::text[],ARRAY['To efficiently compute the gradient of the loss with respect to every weight using the chain rule','To choose the best activation function for each layer automatically','To split the dataset into training and test sets','To increase the learning rate when training slows down']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Backpropagation applies the chain rule backward through the network to compute each weight''s gradient efficiently so gradient descent can update them.','Backpropagation applies the chain rule backward through the network to compute each weight''s gradient efficiently so gradient descent can update them.','Backpropagation calculates how much each weight contributed to the network''s error by propagating the loss backward layer by layer. It reuses intermediate results via the chain rule of calculus, making gradient computation efficient even for millions of parameters. These gradients are then fed to an optimizer such as gradient descent, which adjusts the weights to reduce the loss.','Backpropagation calculates how much each weight contributed to the network''s error by propagating the loss backward layer by layer. It reuses intermediate results via the chain rule of calculus, making gradient computation efficient even for millions of parameters. These gradients are then fed to an optimizer such as gradient descent, which adjusts the weights to reduce the loss.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-llms-1','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-1','beginner','mcq','When a large language model processes text, what is a ''token''?','When a large language model processes text, what is a ''token''?',ARRAY['A chunk of text such as a word or word-piece that the model reads and predicts','A security key that authorizes the API request','A single pixel in an input image','The model''s final confidence score for an answer']::text[],ARRAY['A chunk of text such as a word or word-piece that the model reads and predicts','A security key that authorizes the API request','A single pixel in an input image','The model''s final confidence score for an answer']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Language models break text into tokens (words or sub-word pieces) as the basic units they read and generate.','Language models break text into tokens (words or sub-word pieces) as the basic units they read and generate.','Tokens are the small pieces of text, often whole words or fragments of words, that a language model operates on. Text is split into tokens before processing, and the model generates output one token at a time. Token counts matter in practice because they determine how much text fits in a request and often how usage is priced.','Tokens are the small pieces of text, often whole words or fragments of words, that a language model operates on. Text is split into tokens before processing, and the model generates output one token at a time. Token counts matter in practice because they determine how much text fits in a request and often how usage is priced.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-llms-2','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-2','intermediate','mcq','Two words that are used in similar contexts, like ''cat'' and ''kitten'', tend to have embeddings that are close together in vector space. What does this illustrate?','Two words that are used in similar contexts, like ''cat'' and ''kitten'', tend to have embeddings that are close together in vector space. What does this illustrate?',ARRAY['Embeddings capture semantic similarity as geometric closeness','Embeddings store the exact spelling of each word','Embeddings are random and carry no meaning','Embeddings only work for numbers, not words']::text[],ARRAY['Embeddings capture semantic similarity as geometric closeness','Embeddings store the exact spelling of each word','Embeddings are random and carry no meaning','Embeddings only work for numbers, not words']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Embeddings map words to vectors so that semantically related words land near each other, which is why ''cat'' and ''kitten'' are close.','Embeddings map words to vectors so that semantically related words land near each other, which is why ''cat'' and ''kitten'' are close.','An embedding is a dense vector of numbers that represents a token or piece of text in a continuous space. Models learn these vectors so that items with similar meaning or usage sit near one another, letting distance and direction encode relationships. This is what lets systems compare meaning, power semantic search, and feed rich representations into transformers.','An embedding is a dense vector of numbers that represents a token or piece of text in a continuous space. Models learn these vectors so that items with similar meaning or usage sit near one another, letting distance and direction encode relationships. This is what lets systems compare meaning, power semantic search, and feed rich representations into transformers.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-llms-3','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-3','advanced','mcq','What key capability did the transformer''s self-attention mechanism introduce that helps models handle long-range relationships in text?','What key capability did the transformer''s self-attention mechanism introduce that helps models handle long-range relationships in text?',ARRAY['Each token can directly weigh and draw information from any other token in the sequence','It processes tokens strictly one at a time in fixed order with no parallelism','It removes the need for any training data','It guarantees the model never makes factual errors']::text[],ARRAY['Each token can directly weigh and draw information from any other token in the sequence','It processes tokens strictly one at a time in fixed order with no parallelism','It removes the need for any training data','It guarantees the model never makes factual errors']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Self-attention lets every token attend to every other token directly, capturing long-range dependencies that earlier sequential models struggled with.','Self-attention lets every token attend to every other token directly, capturing long-range dependencies that earlier sequential models struggled with.','The transformer architecture relies on self-attention, where each token computes how relevant every other token is and blends in their information accordingly. This direct any-to-any connectivity captures long-range context that older recurrent models handled poorly, and it parallelizes well across hardware. Self-attention is the backbone of modern large language models and a major reason they scale effectively.','The transformer architecture relies on self-attention, where each token computes how relevant every other token is and blends in their information accordingly. This direct any-to-any connectivity captures long-range context that older recurrent models handled poorly, and it parallelizes well across hardware. Self-attention is the backbone of modern large language models and a major reason they scale effectively.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-prompting-1','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-1','beginner','mcq','In a language model, raising the ''temperature'' setting generally has what effect on the generated text?','In a language model, raising the ''temperature'' setting generally has what effect on the generated text?',ARRAY['It makes outputs more random and varied','It makes outputs more repetitive and deterministic','It increases the model''s factual accuracy','It shortens the maximum response length']::text[],ARRAY['It makes outputs more random and varied','It makes outputs more repetitive and deterministic','It increases the model''s factual accuracy','It shortens the maximum response length']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Higher temperature flattens the probability distribution over next tokens, producing more random and diverse text.','Higher temperature flattens the probability distribution over next tokens, producing more random and diverse text.','Temperature is a sampling setting that controls how a model picks the next token from its predicted probabilities. Low temperature concentrates choices on the most likely tokens, giving focused and repeatable output, while high temperature spreads probability out, yielding more creative or surprising text. Choosing a value trades off reliability against variety depending on the task.','Temperature is a sampling setting that controls how a model picks the next token from its predicted probabilities. Low temperature concentrates choices on the most likely tokens, giving focused and repeatable output, while high temperature spreads probability out, yielding more creative or surprising text. Choosing a value trades off reliability against variety depending on the task.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-prompting-2','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-2','intermediate','mcq','A model confidently states a made-up citation that does not exist. In the context of language models, this behavior is best described as what?','A model confidently states a made-up citation that does not exist. In the context of language models, this behavior is best described as what?',ARRAY['A hallucination','A train-test split','An activation function','A clustering error']::text[],ARRAY['A hallucination','A train-test split','An activation function','A clustering error']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Generating fluent but false or fabricated information is known as hallucination in language models.','Generating fluent but false or fabricated information is known as hallucination in language models.','Hallucination is when a language model produces confident-sounding text that is factually wrong or entirely invented. It arises because the model predicts plausible continuations rather than retrieving verified facts. Grounding responses in trusted sources, asking for citations you can check, and evaluating outputs carefully all help reduce the impact of hallucinations.','Hallucination is when a language model produces confident-sounding text that is factually wrong or entirely invented. It arises because the model predicts plausible continuations rather than retrieving verified facts. Grounding responses in trusted sources, asking for citations you can check, and evaluating outputs carefully all help reduce the impact of hallucinations.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-prompting-3','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-3','advanced','mcq','A team adds retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) to their chatbot, which fits within the model''s limited context window. What primary benefit does RAG provide?','A team adds retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) to their chatbot, which fits within the model''s limited context window. What primary benefit does RAG provide?',ARRAY['It supplies relevant external documents at query time so answers are grounded in current, specific information','It permanently retrains the model''s weights on every user question','It removes the need to evaluate the system''s outputs','It eliminates the model''s context window limit entirely']::text[],ARRAY['It supplies relevant external documents at query time so answers are grounded in current, specific information','It permanently retrains the model''s weights on every user question','It removes the need to evaluate the system''s outputs','It eliminates the model''s context window limit entirely']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'RAG retrieves relevant documents and inserts them into the prompt so the model can ground answers in external, up-to-date information without retraining.','RAG retrieves relevant documents and inserts them into the prompt so the model can ground answers in external, up-to-date information without retraining.','Retrieval-augmented generation pairs a language model with a search step that fetches relevant text from an external knowledge source and adds it to the prompt. This grounds responses in specific or current information the model was not trained on, reducing hallucination. Because models have a finite context window, retrieval must select only the most relevant passages, and outputs should still be evaluated for accuracy.','Retrieval-augmented generation pairs a language model with a search step that fetches relevant text from an external knowledge source and adds it to the prompt. This grounds responses in specific or current information the model was not trained on, reducing hallucination. Because models have a finite context window, retrieval must select only the most relevant passages, and outputs should still be evaluated for accuracy.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-mechanics-1','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-1','beginner','mcq','A crate sits still on a flat floor. According to Newton''s first law, what is the net force acting on the crate?','A crate sits still on a flat floor. According to Newton''s first law, what is the net force acting on the crate?',ARRAY['Zero','Equal to its weight, pointing down','Equal to its weight, pointing up','Equal to the friction force, pointing sideways']::text[],ARRAY['Zero','Equal to its weight, pointing down','Equal to its weight, pointing up','Equal to the friction force, pointing sideways']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'An object at rest has zero acceleration, so by Newton''s first law the net force on it must be zero.','An object at rest has zero acceleration, so by Newton''s first law the net force on it must be zero.','Newton''s first law says an object stays at rest or in uniform motion unless a net force acts on it. When a crate sits still, the downward weight and the upward normal force from the floor are equal and opposite, so they cancel. The net force is the vector sum of all forces, and here that sum is zero.','Newton''s first law says an object stays at rest or in uniform motion unless a net force acts on it. When a crate sits still, the downward weight and the upward normal force from the floor are equal and opposite, so they cancel. The net force is the vector sum of all forces, and here that sum is zero.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-mechanics-2','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-2','intermediate','mcq','A net force of 12 N is applied to a 4 kg object on a frictionless surface. Using Newton''s second law, what is the object''s acceleration?','A net force of 12 N is applied to a 4 kg object on a frictionless surface. Using Newton''s second law, what is the object''s acceleration?',ARRAY['3 m/s^2','48 m/s^2','8 m/s^2','0.33 m/s^2']::text[],ARRAY['3 m/s^2','48 m/s^2','8 m/s^2','0.33 m/s^2']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Newton''s second law gives a = F/m = 12 N / 4 kg = 3 m/s^2.','Newton''s second law gives a = F/m = 12 N / 4 kg = 3 m/s^2.','Newton''s second law states that net force equals mass times acceleration (F = ma). Rearranged, acceleration is force divided by mass (a = F/m). A larger force produces more acceleration, while a larger mass resists acceleration, which is why heavier objects are harder to speed up.','Newton''s second law states that net force equals mass times acceleration (F = ma). Rearranged, acceleration is force divided by mass (a = F/m). A larger force produces more acceleration, while a larger mass resists acceleration, which is why heavier objects are harder to speed up.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-mechanics-3','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-3','advanced','mcq','A cable is rated to break at 6000 N and is used to support a static load of 1500 N. What is the factor of safety?','A cable is rated to break at 6000 N and is used to support a static load of 1500 N. What is the factor of safety?',ARRAY['4','0.25','4500','2']::text[],ARRAY['4','0.25','4500','2']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Factor of safety = breaking (ultimate) load / applied load = 6000 N / 1500 N = 4.','Factor of safety = breaking (ultimate) load / applied load = 6000 N / 1500 N = 4.','The factor of safety compares a component''s failure capacity to the load it actually carries, computed as ultimate strength divided by working load. A value greater than 1 means the part can withstand more than is demanded, giving a margin against overloads, defects, and uncertainty. Engineers choose higher factors for critical or unpredictable applications and lower ones where weight or cost matters and conditions are well understood.','The factor of safety compares a component''s failure capacity to the load it actually carries, computed as ultimate strength divided by working load. A value greater than 1 means the part can withstand more than is demanded, giving a margin against overloads, defects, and uncertainty. Engineers choose higher factors for critical or unpredictable applications and lower ones where weight or cost matters and conditions are well understood.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-circuits-1','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-1','beginner','mcq','In a simple circuit, a 12 V source drives a current through a 6 ohm resistor. Using Ohm''s law, what current flows?','In a simple circuit, a 12 V source drives a current through a 6 ohm resistor. Using Ohm''s law, what current flows?',ARRAY['2 A','72 A','0.5 A','18 A']::text[],ARRAY['2 A','72 A','0.5 A','18 A']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Ohm''s law gives I = V / R = 12 V / 6 ohm = 2 A.','Ohm''s law gives I = V / R = 12 V / 6 ohm = 2 A.','Ohm''s law relates voltage, current, and resistance as V = IR. Rearranged, current equals voltage divided by resistance (I = V/R). Higher voltage pushes more current, while higher resistance restricts it, much like water pressure and pipe width affect flow.','Ohm''s law relates voltage, current, and resistance as V = IR. Rearranged, current equals voltage divided by resistance (I = V/R). Higher voltage pushes more current, while higher resistance restricts it, much like water pressure and pipe width affect flow.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-circuits-2','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-2','intermediate','mcq','Two resistors of 4 ohm and 6 ohm are connected in series across a battery. What is their total resistance?','Two resistors of 4 ohm and 6 ohm are connected in series across a battery. What is their total resistance?',ARRAY['10 ohm','2.4 ohm','24 ohm','5 ohm']::text[],ARRAY['10 ohm','2.4 ohm','24 ohm','5 ohm']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Resistances in series simply add: 4 ohm + 6 ohm = 10 ohm.','Resistances in series simply add: 4 ohm + 6 ohm = 10 ohm.','When resistors are connected in series, the same current flows through each one and their resistances add to give the total. This is because the current must pass through every resistor in turn, so each adds its own opposition. In contrast, resistors in parallel give a total resistance smaller than the smallest individual resistor.','When resistors are connected in series, the same current flows through each one and their resistances add to give the total. This is because the current must pass through every resistor in turn, so each adds its own opposition. In contrast, resistors in parallel give a total resistance smaller than the smallest individual resistor.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-circuits-3','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-3','advanced','mcq','A resistor carries 0.5 A of current with 8 V across it. Using P = VI, how much power does it dissipate?','A resistor carries 0.5 A of current with 8 V across it. Using P = VI, how much power does it dissipate?',ARRAY['4 W','16 W','8.5 W','0.0625 W']::text[],ARRAY['4 W','16 W','8.5 W','0.0625 W']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Power equals voltage times current: P = VI = 8 V x 0.5 A = 4 W.','Power equals voltage times current: P = VI = 8 V x 0.5 A = 4 W.','Electrical power is the rate at which energy is delivered or dissipated, given by P = VI for a component. For a resistor this energy turns into heat, which is why resistors and wires warm up under load. Using Ohm''s law you can also write this as P = I^2 R or P = V^2 / R, which all give the same result.','Electrical power is the rate at which energy is delivered or dissipated, given by P = VI for a component. For a resistor this energy turns into heat, which is why resistors and wires warm up under load. Using Ohm''s law you can also write this as P = I^2 R or P = V^2 / R, which all give the same result.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-algorithms-1','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-1','beginner','truefalse','A linear search scans a list one element at a time from the start until it finds the target or reaches the end. Its worst-case time complexity is O(n).','A linear search scans a list one element at a time from the start until it finds the target or reaches the end. Its worst-case time complexity is O(n).',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'In the worst case the target is last or absent, so a linear search must check all n elements, giving O(n).','In the worst case the target is last or absent, so a linear search must check all n elements, giving O(n).','Big-O notation describes how an algorithm''s running time grows as the input size n increases, focusing on the dominant term. Linear search examines each element once, so in the worst case it does work proportional to n, written O(n). Algorithms that grow more slowly, like O(log n), become much faster than linear search for large inputs.','Big-O notation describes how an algorithm''s running time grows as the input size n increases, focusing on the dominant term. Linear search examines each element once, so in the worst case it does work proportional to n, written O(n). Algorithms that grow more slowly, like O(log n), become much faster than linear search for large inputs.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-algorithms-2','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-2','intermediate','mcq','What is the worst-case time complexity of binary search on a sorted array of n elements?','What is the worst-case time complexity of binary search on a sorted array of n elements?',ARRAY['O(log n)','O(n)','O(n log n)','O(1)']::text[],ARRAY['O(log n)','O(n)','O(n log n)','O(1)']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Binary search halves the remaining range each step, so it takes about log base 2 of n comparisons, giving O(log n).','Binary search halves the remaining range each step, so it takes about log base 2 of n comparisons, giving O(log n).','Binary search works only on sorted data and repeatedly compares the target to the middle element, discarding half the remaining elements each time. Because the search space halves every step, the number of comparisons grows like the logarithm of n. This makes it dramatically faster than linear search for large sorted collections.','Binary search works only on sorted data and repeatedly compares the target to the middle element, discarding half the remaining elements each time. Because the search space halves every step, the number of comparisons grows like the logarithm of n. This makes it dramatically faster than linear search for large sorted collections.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-algorithms-3','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-3','advanced','mcq','An algorithm uses two nested loops, each iterating over all n elements of an input, doing constant work inside. What is its time complexity?','An algorithm uses two nested loops, each iterating over all n elements of an input, doing constant work inside. What is its time complexity?',ARRAY['O(n^2)','O(n)','O(2n)','O(log n)']::text[],ARRAY['O(n^2)','O(n)','O(2n)','O(log n)']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'An inner loop of n iterations runs for each of the n outer iterations, giving n x n = n^2 operations, or O(n^2).','An inner loop of n iterations runs for each of the n outer iterations, giving n x n = n^2 operations, or O(n^2).','Nested loops multiply their iteration counts, so two loops each running n times perform on the order of n^2 operations. Quadratic algorithms scale poorly: doubling the input roughly quadruples the work. Recognizing nested-loop patterns helps engineers spot performance bottlenecks and seek more efficient approaches for large inputs.','Nested loops multiply their iteration counts, so two loops each running n times perform on the order of n^2 operations. Quadratic algorithms scale poorly: doubling the input roughly quadruples the work. Recognizing nested-loop patterns helps engineers spot performance bottlenecks and seek more efficient approaches for large inputs.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-reliability-1','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-1','beginner','mcq','In SI units, which unit measures force?','In SI units, which unit measures force?',ARRAY['Newton','Joule','Watt','Pascal']::text[],ARRAY['Newton','Joule','Watt','Pascal']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The newton (N) is the SI unit of force, defined as the force that accelerates 1 kg at 1 m/s^2.','The newton (N) is the SI unit of force, defined as the force that accelerates 1 kg at 1 m/s^2.','The International System of Units (SI) defines standard units so engineers worldwide can communicate measurements unambiguously. The newton measures force, the joule measures energy, the watt measures power, and the pascal measures pressure. Each derived unit is built from the base units like the kilogram, meter, and second.','The International System of Units (SI) defines standard units so engineers worldwide can communicate measurements unambiguously. The newton measures force, the joule measures energy, the watt measures power, and the pascal measures pressure. Each derived unit is built from the base units like the kilogram, meter, and second.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-reliability-2','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-2','intermediate','mcq','A service is available 99% of the time over a 30-day month. Approximately how much total downtime does that allow?','A service is available 99% of the time over a 30-day month. Approximately how much total downtime does that allow?',ARRAY['About 7.2 hours','About 43 minutes','About 3 days','About 22 minutes']::text[],ARRAY['About 7.2 hours','About 43 minutes','About 3 days','About 22 minutes']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A 30-day month is 720 hours, and 1% of 720 hours is 7.2 hours of allowed downtime.','A 30-day month is 720 hours, and 1% of 720 hours is 7.2 hours of allowed downtime.','Availability is the fraction of time a system is operational, often quoted as a percentage like 99% (''two nines''). Downtime is the remaining fraction multiplied by the total time period. Adding more nines shrinks allowed downtime sharply: 99.9% over the same 30 days allows only about 43 minutes.','Availability is the fraction of time a system is operational, often quoted as a percentage like 99% (''two nines''). Downtime is the remaining fraction multiplied by the total time period. Adding more nines shrinks allowed downtime sharply: 99.9% over the same 30 days allows only about 43 minutes.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-reliability-3','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-3','advanced','mcq','Two independent components are in series, each with a reliability (probability of working) of 0.9. What is the overall reliability of the system?','Two independent components are in series, each with a reliability (probability of working) of 0.9. What is the overall reliability of the system?',ARRAY['0.81','0.9','0.99','1.8']::text[],ARRAY['0.81','0.9','0.99','1.8']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'For independent components in series, reliabilities multiply: 0.9 x 0.9 = 0.81.','For independent components in series, reliabilities multiply: 0.9 x 0.9 = 0.81.','In a series reliability model, the system works only if every component works, so the overall reliability is the product of the individual reliabilities. Because each value is less than 1, adding more series components always lowers total reliability. Designers improve reliability by adding redundancy in parallel, where the system survives as long as at least one path works.','In a series reliability model, the system works only if every component works, so the overall reliability is the product of the individual reliabilities. Because each value is less than 1, adding more series components always lowers total reliability. Designers improve reliability by adding redundancy in parallel, where the system survives as long as at least one path works.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-openings-1','chess','chess:openings','chess-openings-1','beginner','mcq','Which of these is a core principle for playing the opening well?','Which of these is a core principle for playing the opening well?',ARRAY['Control the center with pawns and pieces','Move your queen out as early as possible','Push the pawns in front of your king before developing','Move the same piece several times to find its best square']::text[],ARRAY['Control the center with pawns and pieces','Move your queen out as early as possible','Push the pawns in front of your king before developing','Move the same piece several times to find its best square']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Controlling the center gives your pieces more mobility and influence over the most important squares on the board.','Controlling the center gives your pieces more mobility and influence over the most important squares on the board.','The four central squares (d4, d5, e4, e5) are the most valuable real estate in chess because pieces placed near them reach the most squares. Strong opening play means fighting for the center with pawns and developing minor pieces to support that fight. Wasting early moves on the queen or repeated piece moves usually loses time and lets the opponent seize the initiative.','The four central squares (d4, d5, e4, e5) are the most valuable real estate in chess because pieces placed near them reach the most squares. Strong opening play means fighting for the center with pawns and developing minor pieces to support that fight. Wasting early moves on the queen or repeated piece moves usually loses time and lets the opponent seize the initiative.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-openings-2','chess','chess:openings','chess-openings-2','intermediate','mcq','After 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3, White attacks Black''s e5 pawn. Which move both develops a piece and defends e5?','After 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3, White attacks Black''s e5 pawn. Which move both develops a piece and defends e5?',ARRAY['2...Nc6','2...a6','2...Qe7','2...d6 followed by no development']::text[],ARRAY['2...Nc6','2...a6','2...Qe7','2...d6 followed by no development']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'2...Nc6 develops the knight toward the center while defending the attacked e5 pawn, achieving two goals in one move.','2...Nc6 develops the knight toward the center while defending the attacked e5 pawn, achieving two goals in one move.','Good opening moves often accomplish more than one thing at once, such as developing a piece while defending a pawn or controlling a key square. 2...Nc6 is the most natural reply because the knight defends e5, fights for the center, and heads to an active square. Passive defenses like 2...Qe7 block your own pieces, while 2...d6 (the Philidor) defends but is more cramped and passive than the knight move.','Good opening moves often accomplish more than one thing at once, such as developing a piece while defending a pawn or controlling a key square. 2...Nc6 is the most natural reply because the knight defends e5, fights for the center, and heads to an active square. Passive defenses like 2...Qe7 block your own pieces, while 2...d6 (the Philidor) defends but is more cramped and passive than the knight move.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-openings-3','chess','chess:openings','chess-openings-3','advanced','mcq','In a gambit such as the King''s Gambit (1.e4 e5 2.f4), what is the player who sacrifices a pawn primarily trying to obtain?','In a gambit such as the King''s Gambit (1.e4 e5 2.f4), what is the player who sacrifices a pawn primarily trying to obtain?',ARRAY['A lead in development and active piece play','An immediate forced checkmate','A material advantage by winning a piece back at once','A locked, drawish pawn structure']::text[],ARRAY['A lead in development and active piece play','An immediate forced checkmate','A material advantage by winning a piece back at once','A locked, drawish pawn structure']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A gambit trades material for a head start in development and open lines, hoping that activity and initiative outweigh the lost pawn.','A gambit trades material for a head start in development and open lines, hoping that activity and initiative outweigh the lost pawn.','A gambit deliberately gives up a pawn (or more) to gain time, open lines, and faster development. The idea is that rapid mobilization and the initiative can be worth more than a single pawn, especially if the defender falls behind. Gambits are double-edged: if the attacker fails to use the activity quickly, the extra pawn can decide the game in the long run.','A gambit deliberately gives up a pawn (or more) to gain time, open lines, and faster development. The idea is that rapid mobilization and the initiative can be worth more than a single pawn, especially if the defender falls behind. Gambits are double-edged: if the attacker fails to use the activity quickly, the extra pawn can decide the game in the long run.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-tactics-1','chess','chess:tactics','chess-tactics-1','beginner','mcq','What is a ''fork'' in chess?','What is a ''fork'' in chess?',ARRAY['One piece attacking two or more enemy pieces at the same time','Trapping a piece against the edge of the board','Trading two pieces for a single stronger piece','Moving a pawn to the last rank to promote it']::text[],ARRAY['One piece attacking two or more enemy pieces at the same time','Trapping a piece against the edge of the board','Trading two pieces for a single stronger piece','Moving a pawn to the last rank to promote it']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A fork is a single move that attacks two or more targets simultaneously, so the opponent cannot save them all.','A fork is a single move that attacks two or more targets simultaneously, so the opponent cannot save them all.','A fork is one of the most common tactics, where a single piece threatens two or more enemy pieces or squares at once. Knights are especially good at forking because they attack in an L-shape that other pieces cannot block. The classic example is a knight that attacks the enemy king and queen together, forcing the king to move and winning the queen.','A fork is one of the most common tactics, where a single piece threatens two or more enemy pieces or squares at once. Knights are especially good at forking because they attack in an L-shape that other pieces cannot block. The classic example is a knight that attacks the enemy king and queen together, forcing the king to move and winning the queen.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-tactics-2','chess','chess:tactics','chess-tactics-2','intermediate','mcq','A pin and a skewer both attack two pieces on the same line. What is the key difference?','A pin and a skewer both attack two pieces on the same line. What is the key difference?',ARRAY['In a skewer the more valuable piece is in front and must move, exposing the piece behind it','A pin can only be made by a knight, while a skewer is made by a bishop','A skewer always attacks the king, while a pin never does','A pin wins material immediately, while a skewer never wins material']::text[],ARRAY['In a skewer the more valuable piece is in front and must move, exposing the piece behind it','A pin can only be made by a knight, while a skewer is made by a bishop','A skewer always attacks the king, while a pin never does','A pin wins material immediately, while a skewer never wins material']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'In a skewer the valuable piece is in front and is forced to move, allowing capture of the lesser piece behind it, which is the reverse of a pin.','In a skewer the valuable piece is in front and is forced to move, allowing capture of the lesser piece behind it, which is the reverse of a pin.','Pins and skewers are line tactics carried out by bishops, rooks, and queens. In a pin, a less valuable (or equally valuable) piece is shielded behind a more valuable one, so it cannot or should not move. A skewer is the inverse: the valuable piece is attacked first and must step aside, exposing the piece behind it to capture.','Pins and skewers are line tactics carried out by bishops, rooks, and queens. In a pin, a less valuable (or equally valuable) piece is shielded behind a more valuable one, so it cannot or should not move. A skewer is the inverse: the valuable piece is attacked first and must step aside, exposing the piece behind it to capture.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-tactics-3','chess','chess:tactics','chess-tactics-3','advanced','mcq','What makes a ''discovered attack'' so dangerous, and especially a discovered check?','What makes a ''discovered attack'' so dangerous, and especially a discovered check?',ARRAY['Moving one piece unveils an attack from another, so two threats appear at once and a discovered check can win material ''for free''','It forces an immediate draw by repetition','It only works when both kings are still on their starting squares','It allows a pawn to capture two pieces in a single move']::text[],ARRAY['Moving one piece unveils an attack from another, so two threats appear at once and a discovered check can win material ''for free''','It forces an immediate draw by repetition','It only works when both kings are still on their starting squares','It allows a pawn to capture two pieces in a single move']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A discovered attack lets the moving piece create its own threat while uncovering a second attacker, and with a discovered check the opponent must respond to the check first, often losing the piece attacked by the moving piece.','A discovered attack lets the moving piece create its own threat while uncovering a second attacker, and with a discovered check the opponent must respond to the check first, often losing the piece attacked by the moving piece.','A discovered attack happens when you move one piece out of the way to reveal an attack from a piece behind it, generating two threats with a single move. The moving piece can capture, attack, or make its own threat while the unveiled piece does its work. A discovered check is the strongest version because the opponent is forced to deal with the check immediately, so the moving piece can grab material or a key square almost unopposed.','A discovered attack happens when you move one piece out of the way to reveal an attack from a piece behind it, generating two threats with a single move. The moving piece can capture, attack, or make its own threat while the unveiled piece does its work. A discovered check is the strongest version because the opponent is forced to deal with the check immediately, so the moving piece can grab material or a key square almost unopposed.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-endgames-1','chess','chess:endgames','chess-endgames-1','beginner','mcq','When a pawn reaches the opponent''s back rank (the far end of the board), what happens?','When a pawn reaches the opponent''s back rank (the far end of the board), what happens?',ARRAY['It promotes and is replaced by a queen, rook, bishop, or knight of the same color','It is removed from the board as a reward','It automatically becomes a second king','It must stay a pawn but can now move backward']::text[],ARRAY['It promotes and is replaced by a queen, rook, bishop, or knight of the same color','It is removed from the board as a reward','It automatically becomes a second king','It must stay a pawn but can now move backward']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A pawn that reaches the last rank must promote, almost always to a queen because the queen is the most powerful piece.','A pawn that reaches the last rank must promote, almost always to a queen because the queen is the most powerful piece.','Promotion is the reason pawns become so important in the endgame: every pawn is a potential queen. When a pawn reaches the eighth rank (or first rank for Black), it is immediately exchanged for a queen, rook, bishop, or knight of the same color. Players almost always choose a queen, but occasionally promote to a knight or another piece to avoid stalemate or to deliver an immediate fork or check.','Promotion is the reason pawns become so important in the endgame: every pawn is a potential queen. When a pawn reaches the eighth rank (or first rank for Black), it is immediately exchanged for a queen, rook, bishop, or knight of the same color. Players almost always choose a queen, but occasionally promote to a knight or another piece to avoid stalemate or to deliver an immediate fork or check.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-endgames-2','chess','chess:endgames','chess-endgames-2','intermediate','mcq','In king and pawn endgames, what does it mean to ''have the opposition''?','In king and pawn endgames, what does it mean to ''have the opposition''?',ARRAY['Your kings face each other with one empty square between them and it is the opponent''s turn to move, forcing their king to give way','You have more pawns than your opponent on the same file','Your king is in check and must move immediately','You control a diagonal with your bishop against the enemy king']::text[],ARRAY['Your kings face each other with one empty square between them and it is the opponent''s turn to move, forcing their king to give way','You have more pawns than your opponent on the same file','Your king is in check and must move immediately','You control a diagonal with your bishop against the enemy king']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Having the opposition means the kings stand directly opposed with one square between them and the other player is on move, so their king must step aside and yield ground.','Having the opposition means the kings stand directly opposed with one square between them and the other player is on move, so their king must step aside and yield ground.','The opposition is a key king-and-pawn endgame technique where the player NOT on the move often controls the position. When the kings stand one square apart and your opponent must move, their king is forced to give way, letting your king advance. Mastering the opposition lets the stronger side escort a pawn to promotion and helps the weaker side hold a draw.','The opposition is a key king-and-pawn endgame technique where the player NOT on the move often controls the position. When the kings stand one square apart and your opponent must move, their king is forced to give way, letting your king advance. Mastering the opposition lets the stronger side escort a pawn to promotion and helps the weaker side hold a draw.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-endgames-3','chess','chess:endgames','chess-endgames-3','advanced','truefalse','A lone king plus a single knight (with no pawns) can force checkmate against a lone king.','A lone king plus a single knight (with no pawns) can force checkmate against a lone king.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],1,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'King and a single knight cannot force checkmate against a lone king; there is insufficient mating material, so the game is drawn.','King and a single knight cannot force checkmate against a lone king; there is insufficient mating material, so the game is drawn.','Some material combinations simply cannot force checkmate against a lone king, which results in a draw by insufficient material. A king and one knight, or a king and one bishop, can never deliver a forced mate. By contrast, king and queen, king and rook, and even the tricky two-bishop or bishop-plus-knight combinations can all force mate with correct play.','Some material combinations simply cannot force checkmate against a lone king, which results in a draw by insufficient material. A king and one knight, or a king and one bishop, can never deliver a forced mate. By contrast, king and queen, king and rook, and even the tricky two-bishop or bishop-plus-knight combinations can all force mate with correct play.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-strategy-1','chess','chess:strategy','chess-strategy-1','beginner','mcq','Using the standard relative piece values, how much is a rook worth?','Using the standard relative piece values, how much is a rook worth?',ARRAY['About 5 points','About 1 point','About 3 points','About 9 points']::text[],ARRAY['About 5 points','About 1 point','About 3 points','About 9 points']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A rook is conventionally valued at about 5 points, more than a minor piece (3) but less than a queen (9).','A rook is conventionally valued at about 5 points, more than a minor piece (3) but less than a queen (9).','The standard point values help you judge trades: pawn 1, knight 3, bishop 3, rook 5, and queen 9. The king has no point value because it can never be captured. These numbers are guidelines rather than absolute rules, since activity, king safety, and pawn structure can make a piece worth more or less than its nominal value in a given position.','The standard point values help you judge trades: pawn 1, knight 3, bishop 3, rook 5, and queen 9. The king has no point value because it can never be captured. These numbers are guidelines rather than absolute rules, since activity, king safety, and pawn structure can make a piece worth more or less than its nominal value in a given position.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-strategy-2','chess','chess:strategy','chess-strategy-2','intermediate','mcq','In chess strategy, what is an ''outpost''?','In chess strategy, what is an ''outpost''?',ARRAY['An advanced square, often protected by a pawn and not attackable by enemy pawns, where a piece like a knight is very strong','A pawn that has no friendly pawns on the files next to it','The square directly in front of the king after castling','Any square on the player''s own first two ranks']::text[],ARRAY['An advanced square, often protected by a pawn and not attackable by enemy pawns, where a piece like a knight is very strong','A pawn that has no friendly pawns on the files next to it','The square directly in front of the king after castling','Any square on the player''s own first two ranks']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'An outpost is a well-protected advanced square that enemy pawns cannot challenge, making it an ideal home for a knight or other piece.','An outpost is a well-protected advanced square that enemy pawns cannot challenge, making it an ideal home for a knight or other piece.','An outpost is a strong square deep in or near the opponent''s territory that cannot be attacked by enemy pawns, usually because those pawns have advanced past it or been traded off. Knights love outposts because once established they cannot easily be driven away and they radiate pressure. Planning your strategy often involves creating an outpost and maneuvering a knight to occupy it.','An outpost is a strong square deep in or near the opponent''s territory that cannot be attacked by enemy pawns, usually because those pawns have advanced past it or been traded off. Knights love outposts because once established they cannot easily be driven away and they radiate pressure. Planning your strategy often involves creating an outpost and maneuvering a knight to occupy it.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-chess-strategy-3','chess','chess:strategy','chess-strategy-3','advanced','mcq','An ''isolated queen''s pawn'' (an isolated pawn on the d-file) is a classic structural feature. What is the typical strategic trade-off it creates?','An ''isolated queen''s pawn'' (an isolated pawn on the d-file) is a classic structural feature. What is the typical strategic trade-off it creates?',ARRAY['It grants active piece play and central space, but is a long-term weakness that can be blockaded and attacked','It guarantees a winning attack in every game','It is always a decisive weakness with no compensation whatsoever','It can never be captured because it sits on the d-file']::text[],ARRAY['It grants active piece play and central space, but is a long-term weakness that can be blockaded and attacked','It guarantees a winning attack in every game','It is always a decisive weakness with no compensation whatsoever','It can never be captured because it sits on the d-file']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'An isolated d-pawn offers space and open lines for active pieces in the middlegame, but because no friendly pawn can defend it, the opponent aims to blockade and eventually win it, especially in the endgame.','An isolated d-pawn offers space and open lines for active pieces in the middlegame, but because no friendly pawn can defend it, the opponent aims to blockade and eventually win it, especially in the endgame.','An isolated pawn has no friendly pawns on the adjacent files, so it can only be defended by pieces, not pawns. The isolated queen''s pawn is the textbook example: its owner gets open lines, central space, and attacking chances in the middlegame, while the opponent tries to neutralize the activity and blockade the pawn on the square in front of it. Whoever understands this trade-off better usually steers the game toward the structure that favors them, the attacker keeping pieces on, the defender trading down toward an endgame.','An isolated pawn has no friendly pawns on the adjacent files, so it can only be defended by pieces, not pawns. The isolated queen''s pawn is the textbook example: its owner gets open lines, central space, and attacking chances in the middlegame, while the opponent tries to neutralize the activity and blockade the pawn on the square in front of it. Whoever understands this trade-off better usually steers the game toward the structure that favors them, the attacker keeping pieces on, the defender trading down toward an endgame.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
